Rayme is a sweet, loving, timid senior lady in search for her forever family. She walks well on a leash but still needs a bit of encouragement in new environments, however she will follow her person anywhere. To meet her fill out an application at

Here at 2DaRescue we value the health and safety of our animals. Our adoption fee is $300 for adult dogs We feed high quality dog food, Costco Kirkland Signature super Premium Chicken and Brown Rice. All of our dogs come spayed/neutered, fully vaccinated with proof, microchipped, 4Dx tested (basic blood work that tests for diseases), currently on monthly preventatives, and dewormed with a board spectrum dewormer.
Located in the Phoenix, Arizona area Please note, we only do in state adoptions!

animal.description:
"Sachi" is a 5 year old Miniature Australian Shepherd who needs to find a new home.  She has been a great dog for the past three years but has now become very bossy and is nipping the children, escaping from the yard, running away from home and being taken to jail.  She is being a typical Mini-Aussie.  They are bossy and nip.  That is their JOB!

"Sachi" is housetrained and does well with other dogs, cats and even herds the domestic rabbits.  She will have to be spayed and brought current on vaccinations before going into a new home.  Her spaying is scheduled for January 15 and thereafter she can go to her new home.

We do not adopt to families with children under the age of 5 and prefer to adopt within a 200 mile radius of the Cody/Powell area.  Her adoption fee is $200 and she will come with her complete vet records, microchip registration and various supplies.

If you are interested in adopting "Sachi" please email kathy@3dogrescue.com for an application that can be filled out online and returned.

animal.description: Meet Ozzy! This sweet 2 yr old boy is dog and kid friendly! House trained. Not a crate fan but can do short stints. Neutered, shots current and will be micro chipped prior to adoption. Application can be found on main site at www.etnpitbullrescue.orgEast TN Pit Bull Rescue adopts out to companion homes only. Adoptions require an application that is verified, a meeting that includes ALL members of the household, a home visit, and a trial period. All of our dogs are placed as inside pets, spayed/neutered, micro chipped, vaccinations current, and HW- or treated within the last 6 months for heart worms by our vet. Adoption fees start at $150 for adults and $200 for pups. If you are interested in offering this pet a responsible and loving home, please fill out the on-line application at www.etnpitbullrescue.org. East TN Pit Bull Rescue is a Tennessee Non-profit corporation with 501(c)(3) status. Your donations to sponsor pets are tax deductible. If you would like to sponsor this pet, please go to www.paypal.com and make a donation to donations@etnpitbullrescue.org OR contact Butler's Animal Clinic at 865-531-7311 to make a donation on the East TN Pit Bull Rescue Account. animal.description:
Jupiter, or JupJup as we call her, is a very sweet natured girl who is about 2 years old and weighs 38 lbs. She has not had an easy life. She lived her first two years on her own as a stray until she was picked up by animal services and was rescued by Furever After just in time to avoid being euthanized. At first she had a slow time adjusting to life inside, but she has really blossomed into a most incredible little girl. She is short and compact and totally adorable. We have only heard one bark ever, so she's a pretty quiet girl. She is crate trained and house trained. She gets better walking on a leash every time she goes out. Jupiter is still young and has bursts of playful energy and would be best in a household with a playmate/fur sibling. She can play rough, so her fur sibling would need to match her size and strength or be a little larger. She is not yet kid or cat tested. She would probably be a little too much for smaller children. 
Inside she would like to have her own special spot or spots to chill in. She is not overly nosy and does not like to explore too much. When she does want to cuddle, she cuddles hard, but she isn't overly affectionate yet. Jup is silly and when she's being playful, she will have you cracking up hard. She does very well eating her dinner in her crate, but would be ok eating anywhere that she can eat alone. She doesn't love being in the crate during the day, but she's working on it. She's good at night in her crate, but would rather be in bed with you. 

In short, Jupiter is a sweet girl who wants to snuggle at night and play with her fur siblings during the day. She would love to find a home where she can feel safe and secure and loved.

If you are interested in giving Jupiter a forever home, please visit the link below to fill out an application! http://fureverafterrescue.org/adoption-application.html It is best to submit an application through a computer. We have experienced some problems when applications have been submitted using a mobile device. *When you submit the application, you are not obligated to adopt however it does reserve for you the opportunity to adopt that particular animal. We review them on a first come first served basis. If your application is approved, we will contact you and allow you the opportunity to adopt. If you choose not to adopt, we will contact the next approved applicant. If you have any questions or difficulties, please contact us we will be glad to help!

Howdy, JJ here! I recently arrived in rescue after my previous owner got very sick and could no longer care for me. I’m approx. 10 years old and overall I feel pretty fit. My Foster Mom says I will be seeing a Vet very soon for a well check and after that will be ready to go to my new furever home. I am potty trained & I sleep well in my own bed through the night. I get along well with other small dogs, but don't care for the bigger ones so much. Foster Mom says while I am one cool little dude, I would do best in a home without small children. You see, I am still a little cautious when being picked up, but I am working on it. I spend my days hanging out in the backyard, sneaking naps in a dark corner, lounging around, going on short walks with my Foster Family, playing with toys & boy howdy, I LOVE mealtime! If you’re interested in me you can start the process by sending in an application to this awesome rescue so my Foster Mom can arrange a meet cute. That's me, I'm cute! Woof!!

Flag, a big sweetheart, that has been in foster care for most of this year.
He is looking for a loving couple/family to call my own.  He is a 5 year old Rottweiler/mix from Texas. 
He loves going on walks, playing in the park, riding in cars, playing with ropes, tennis balls, chewing on bones, or just wanting to be petted or cuddled.
He would be very happy in a home with lots of daily exercise! When it comes to other dogs, he gets along with most. Flag does NOT get along with cats.  Overall he is a very happy guy!
He is about 60lbs. up to date on my shots, and even microchipped!
He will need to be the only dog in the home.
He is living in the Sheboygan county area if you'd love to meet him! 

***UPDATE 12.24.20 :  Flag - Adoption Fee Sponsored!
Flag has been waiting for the right person to rescue him and we had hope that a Veteran looking for a companion would be a great match.  No one came forward so now we are opening the application to all people. Flag's family must be out there somewhere!
Flag is a happy and loving guy.  He has a good amount of energy and would love to join you for adventures, car rides and walks.  Flag would need a home without cats.  He gets along with most dogs, but would be best to be the only pet.  
Flag is 60lb, 5year old Rottweiler Mix 
Being Fostered in Sheboygan county area
Adoption Fee has been generously sponsored  -  foster will determine best match for Flag

Bisquits is a puppy born 07/07/20 looking for her forever home! She and her sister Gravy were found outside of a restaurant in Mobile when they were two weeks old and luckily sent to rescue. Gravy has found an amazing home and now it is Bisquits' turn!

Bisquits is smart, sweet, and kennel trained. She has picked up commands easily and will thrive with a family/Individual that will continue her training. She is a wiggle butt aka she has a nub instead of a tail! She is almost completely potty trained but still has some accidents. She has been very well socialized in her foster home, getting along with dogs of all sizes and even cats. Her foster mom says she loves to chew on bones and play with toys! She will sit on your lap and receive tummy rubs and give kisses forever!! She is pretty vocal so might not be great for apartment living and she must have another dog in her home to help keep her out of trouble... or join in.

animal.description: A beautiful BIG Shepherd mix who needs some training and exercise. He's young, he's playful, he's energetic, and he's a shepherd...put those together and you get trouble in the wrong home. In the right homes these guys just flourish. Wylie needs a strong owner able to handle him. He's good with other dogs but on initial meetings he can be quite pushy, so a dog able to tolerate and deflect that into playtime is ideal. He grew up with cats, but likes to try to get them to run so he can be pushy with cats as well. With another young dog to help him play, get some energy used up, he's not as bad...but if he's been cooped up without a playmate or exercise he gets more and more amped up. He's gorgeous, just turned 2 years old. He has quite the potential to be an amazing dog, but he will require some work to get there. At Autumn Acres Animal Rescue we believe each individual animal matters. We take in special cases some of which will stay with us as a sanctuary dog.If the animal is listed as a Socially Imperfect Dog this means they have special needs and special requirements for potential adopters.If the animal is listed as a Socially Imperfect RESIDENT this animal is NOT available for adoption and is one of our sanctuary residents. We list them on our sites because they still matter and they still need donations to help with their long term care.Check out our website for more information: http://www.autumnacres.org

animal.description: Happy continued National Pit Bull Awareness month on this lovely Train-A-Bull Thursday! Do y'all know how easily these puppers learn things? Introducing Mags......she's a youngster at barely one year old. Gal is hyper and distracted and dog reactive in the kennel/kennel area. This was my first time meeting her and I was already thinking, "yikes! I may have to skip to next week's dog because she's never gonna sit still!!" (Side note, Tank, who WAS up for his debut today got adopted!!) Moving on. :) After letting Mags explore the living room area, we got down to business to see what tricks she had up her sleeve. Well, not many, but just look at the focus on that poochie's face when I did have her attention! Tasty treats helped, too. Dogs, especially pitties LOVE TO BE TOLD WHAT TO DO!!! They need it! They must know that they are not in charge, that you are, and when you establish that relationship, these puppers are some of the most loyal, well behaved and loving pets. You don't have to yell, but be firm and consistent and praise, praise praise when they get a command right! Also, about 10 minutes is max time for a training session. And it's been said that's equivalent to 30 minutes of physical exercise (imagine how fit you're gonna be!! ????) Mags' adoption fee (and all her pit mix friends) has been reduced to $49 until the end of October

animal.description: Through no fault of her own, Ellie is looking for a new home. With her family displaced and multiple housing falling through, she's been in boarding for 6 months. Her mommy worries everyday about her quality of life and knows that she's not happy being in a kennel. With no housing opportunities in sight, Ellie's well-being is the utmost priority. Ellie is quite the character. She's a 9 year old bull terrier mix. She absolutely loves being around her people and enjoys chewing on her bones. Overall, she's a mellow pup that loves to relax in her beds (yes, she has multiple ones around the house haha) but does get her nighttime zoomies. After her best friend and older brother passed 2 years ago, she hasn't been accepting of other dogs. She is protective over her people and doesn't like when strange animals come near. She thinks she's a little dog, not some 55 pounds of muscle, and therefore would do best in a home with no small children. They also give her a lot of anxiety since they're loud and all over the place. She does get excited easily so a low key home without a lot of foot traffic would be ideal. She needs a family who is going to be patient and allow her a few weeks to get settled. She does have anxiety and allergies but her mom is willing to sponsor her adoption fee and allergy medication for life. Her mom just wants her to be happy and is determined to find the perfect home for her. Ellie's adoption includes spaying, micro chipping and up to date shots. Please contact Outreach@sjras.org to help Ellie.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Independent, Affectionate, Six Years Old.Hershey is a dog that would be a good fit for a couple without kids. While never aggressive with kids, she has tolerance issues kids may violate. She does get along with other dogs. She is by nature, independent.

She loves to snuggle with her human. She thinks she is a lap pet - and she is not that big s- o for a big lap she is good. She is very affectionate, beautiful and deserves respect at 6 years old. She loves to be pet and massaged. You can move her with a leash on her without any issue. She can be resource guarding but is easily redirected. If you are looking for an affectionate companion that you can treat as a respected family member Hershey is for you. She is crate trained but prefers a bed.

She is not agreeable to being pulled by the collar or forced to do something she does not want to do. She does not like being picked up. She will nip if put in these situations. At her age - she is well behaved enough to know what is right. So force or coercion is unnecessary.

All dogs and puppies are fully wormed, receive rabies and core vaccinations, microchipped, behavior assessed with other dogs and humans (sorry, no cat testing is done here), spend a minimum of 3 weeks free-ranging within a pack of 30 dogs to grow confidence and trust and may have DNA results. All dogs receive lifetime behavior support and can be returned anytime without a fee.

PLEASE NOTE: You MUST complete an adoption application in order to see or adopt a dog from us. The completed adoption application ensures your 'spot' in order of adoption. Emailing/calling with questions will delay your adoption process. ADOPTION APPLICATION --> www.petsreturnhome.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Braxton was sadly found as a stray puppy no one ever came looking for. He is seven months old as of mid Jan '21 and about 35-40 lbs so not going to get much bigger. He is super sweet, loves attention and people and is very playful.
ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.

The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html

IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

All dogs are microchipped, neutered, current on all vaccines, heartworm tested and started on Tri Heart Plus; Vectra 3D.

All household members and any dogs from the household need to be present at the time of the adoption.

Our website is always kept 100% up to date with who is currently available.  As soon as animals are adopted, they are moved to the Adopted Pets page so if they are still listed on the Adoptable Dogs or Cats page, they are still available. So keep any eye on the site for any animals being added as available for adoption as new animals are added everyday! We would recommend if you haven’t done so already that you submit a general online adoption application with us so it is on file for when you are ready to come out and adopt. The adoption counselors will be able to show you many that would be a good fit for your family. Animal House Shelter can not guarantee breed or breed mix of our adoptable animals. The animals are posted on the website as a breed or breed mix based on their physical characteristics they most resemble. We also can not guarantee the ages of our adoptable animals or how large puppies will be when fully grown.

McLovin is a laid back guy that likes to chill out around the home or office and go for an occasional walk or hike. He is on the smaller side about 45-50lbs and fits in an averaged sized lap. He would be a good fit for active senior humans who are looking for a lad back well behaved personality. McLovin doesn't really like being left alone but he tolerates it. He has not been cat tested at this time but can be introduced to the resident calm senior cat on premise, at a request with an approved application. animal.description:
We love Lucy and her sweet personality so much! She loves to snuggle and by snuggle I mean spoon! Lol. She is a bed hog / couch hog for real!

She loves to play, and she plays hard! She can shred toys like an industrial shredder. Kong is best for her, for sure.

She LOVES her foster brother Copper and would do great with a dog brother . I do not know how she is around cats, as we don't have any.

She does not have any idea how fast or heavy she is. She runs full force and with much joy towards what she wants to see! She is learning to slow down and to give more space to people she meets, however she also doesn't have a clue what personal space is. She loves kids, but gets right up close and personal, sometimes knocking them over. We are working on that as well.

She has learned to sit, lay down and shake since we brought her home. She is VERY smart and can escape a kennel if its not closed properly.

We are working on walking on a leash and stay.

She is investigative and likes to look on the counters. She has only retrieved a wooden spoon to chew on and a bagel.

She loves belly rubs and head pats and kisses. She is also a TALKER!! She does not like to be ignored. She will let you know that she desires you attention by starting with a small sigh and get louder until you talk to her. 

She is fantastic! Would do great with an active family. She often plays in the house by herself for entertainment.

animal.description:
Kobe is a loving, shy boy who needs time to slowly open up to humans. Once he warms up and starts to know you, he is all in with unconditional love and trust! Kobe is highly intelligent and trainable. He needs to be the only dog in the house as he is dog selective and likes who he likes. He loves to lead an active lifestyle, so a backyard is ideal and a family who is active. Kobe is very protective of his family and very loyal to those he loves. He also enjoys long walks and needs a little leash training with his dog selective behavior. In the house, Kobe is house trained and loves playing with his toys and bones! Please give this sweet boy a chance to lounge in your house and play in your yard with you! 

If interested in adopting Kobe, kindly fill out the application found here:  

https://www.ozzieandfriendsrescue.org/adoptions

In filling out this adoption application, I understand that Ozzie and Friends Rescue cannot guarantee that the dog applied for is yours to adopt upon completion of application. 

We also want to disclaim that all dogs are rescued so we cannot 100% know the exact breed.

All dogs are spayed or neutered, receive a 24Petwatch microchip, collar, Luzerne County License, and their first (in a series) of shots as part of the shelter’s $120 adoption donation fee. While some pets will have brief or even detailed descriptions, not all pets will have this. As we learn more about the pets in our care descriptions are added by those volunteers. animal.description: Hi! My name is Mouse. My foster mom says it fits me perfectly because I can be timid like a little mouse. I am quite shy with new people but once I get to know you, I love to roll over for tummy rubs and I like to curl up next to you in bed. I will definitely need to be in a home with another dog that will be my buddy. I am very attached to my foster brother, Sky, and I learn a lot about how to dog from him. I didn't have much socialization when I was younger and my foster mom has been working on that with me. She says I am leaps and bounds more confident than I used to be but she also says I will need a special person to understand my quirky personality. I like to chew and can't be left unattended for long periods of time but I do enjoy my crate when my foster mom goes to work if you put a nice chew toy in there with me. I do pretty well going potty outside but I do occassionaly have an accident in the house. As long as I'm on a pretty consistant routine, I do well. I'm a silly, sweet, special girl and I can't wait to find my furever home!

animal.description: KENT is a 2-3 year old #islandterrier from St Croix who has a really sad story, at no fault of his own. He was originally adopted by a family as a puppy, and then returned at a year old because he was "too big." In January Kent was adopted again, but sadly has been returned again due to unforeseen circumstances in which his adopter was unable to continue caring for him. Kent is playful and loving. He loves to take walks, but is easily triggered by the sights and sounds of his environment. He can be nervous with new people and needs a very calm and patient introduction. He is not suited for urban life, and would do best in a quiet home with a fenced-in yard and no kids or other animals. Kent is currently with our trainer in Ohio working on gaining confidence and general obedience. When his professional training is complete he will need someone who will continue his training and provide him with the stability, patience and love that he so deserves after all he's been through.

animal.description:
It's "Mr. Steal Your Girl", Jerry! 

After running from Animal Control for 3 days, Jerry finally made his way to Underdogs with badly burned paw pads, lots of scaries, and struggling to understand he was truly safe. Though Jerry is BIG on showing love to his current foster family, he's been very slow to open up and show us his full personality. He is a true "velcro dog", wanting to make sure he knows where everyone is all the time and is a very close talker (which is probably so he's at the ready when he wants to give kisses - which is always). 

At 4 years old and 75lbs, Jerry thinks himself of a lap dog and has been working hard on training at his foster house. He's mastered "sit", loves the dog door, and is just figuring out how to curb his next level excitement when he thinks it's time to go for a walk or ride. Jerry would do best in a home with older children, mostly since he just doesn't know his size, but will offer up his belly to just about anyone he meets. 

Jerry is absolute perfection and is working hard on some reactivity with other dogs (cats are a "no go" for this sweet boy) - while not all other dogs are his favorite, he absolutely adores his foster sister so it just needs to be the right fit with a lower energy, confident dog. He showers his foster sister with kisses, cuddles and is happy to accompany her when she gets the zoomies - the boy just loves to love! 

Jerry would benefit from a compassionate owner, dedicated to continuing with force-free training to help him gain confidence and feel more secure in his home environment. He's a pretty snoozy hippo who isn't bothered if he doesn't have a ton of physical activity, enjoying daily walks which lead to big naps, being mostly happy with pets from his humans and sunbathing like the Adonis that he is.

Jerry is neutered, up-to-date on basic vaccinations and microchipped. Our Underdogs adult dog adoption fee is $300, which includes spay/neuter, microchip, and up-to-date vaccinations. 

If you're interested in adopting Jerry, please fill out an adoption application here: https://underdogsrescue.org/adopt-form/

Underdogs is a small volunteer-based animal rescue and we unfortunately do not have the resources to respond to phone and email inquires about our adoptable animals at this time. If you're interested in learning more or setting up a meeting with one of our animals, please complete an adoption application first. It may take up to two weeks for application review and one of our coordinators will reach out to you as soon as we are through the intitial review process. We appreciate your patience and understanding! Thank you!

animal.description:
Danny came to us after his owner sadly passed away, leaving he and his 3 canine siblings (who are with other rescues) to fend for thenselves. Understandably, Danny is a bit unsure of new people and new places, but he is coming along well. He LOVES to play with other dogs and listens very well, but will duck away a little when you try to pet him. His foster is working hard to help him learn that people can be kind and belly rubs are the best!

**This dog is heartworm positive and will be treated by the rescue and will be available for foster to adopt for a local to Charleston, SC family that is comfortable with the activity restriction requirements for the duration of treatment.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out an application. We do allow out of state adoptions and any transport costs are at the expense of the adopter. If you have further questions about this dog, please email us at ccradopt@gmail.com and someone will be in touch as soon as possible. Please note we are unable to hold dogs for adopters as this ties up valuable foster homes.

Please understand that we are an all volunteer group and we have jobs outside of this organization. We do our best to provide quick responses but occasionally they are a little slower. If you do not receive a response in 48 hours, please resend to make sure it's received.

Pit Bull / American Staff Terrier

Note from her Foster Mom:
Luna is a wonderful dog! She is affectionate and enjoys being with people. Also, Luna is well-behaved – she is housetrained, responds to commands, takes treats gently and knows “sit” and “paw”. Luna has a medium energy level; she will rest when inside and self-entertain with her toys, yet she thoroughly enjoys a game of fetch and will allow the toy to be taken out of her mouth.

Luna will bark at passersby from behind a fence, yet she quickly gets used to neighboring people and dogs and does not bark at them.
Luna has a youthful and upbeat spirit. Luna's forever family will be so happy to have such a loving dog."

animal.description: Abu is a lovely 1-year-old mixed-breed girl who currently weighs about 70 pounds. She came to SFAS as a transfer from another shelter. Here at the shelter, Abu has been great with staff, she loves to give lots of kisses and is a very sweet and joyfull girl. She does participate in playgroup and is known to be a high energy player. We do ask you to bring your dog in to meet her during your appointment. Abu's adoption fee is $130. She is spayed and microchipped and has age-appropriate vaccinations. A licensing/microchip fee may apply. To meet Abu or to be added to her waitlist, call (505) 983-4309 x 1610 and leave a voicemail message that includes the DOG'S NAME, plus YOUR NAME and A GOOD PHONE NUMBER - OR e-mail this information to adoption@sfhumanesociety.org. A scheduler will call you back within 48 hours to confirm your request. If you have other dogs at home, tell the scheduler you would like to bring them along for a Meet n' Greet. SFAS offers a variety of excellent training classes, seminars and Trainer Talks led by animal behavior professionals. These are half-price for animals adopted from any shelter or rescue group! Due to current COVID-19 restrictions, classes and talks are all presented virtually using Zoom. For course descriptions, schedules and registration, visit https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/group-training-classes/ for classes and https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/special-seminars-and-workshops/ for seminars and Trainer Talks.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting Piglet, please email kat.sanders@lostdogrescue.org

Are you a fan of thrash metal music? Love a set of electric drums, or perhaps you live next to the biggest fireworks display of the year? Not the ideal home setting for most dogs but if you're also the loudest snorer you know, not only will Piglet not mind - he will challenge you for the title! 

Piglet is deaf. But that's not his only superpower. He is also blessed with the ability to read faces, understand hand signals and has a super-canine powered sniffer that can detect a hot dog at 100 meters. His 'drop and wiggle' move for human cuddles is unrivalled although he doesn't always appreciate, that at 90lbs, he's not the ideal lap dog.
 
Piglet has a lot in common with his namesake character from the 100 acre wood. A heart the size of a lion, the most loyal and loving friend , he can rock a green striped sweater and is always willing to just sit with you and contemplate the finer things in life.

He needs a calm, adult only home without children as he can be easily startled and when excited becomes a well-intentioned wrecking ball! Despite his sweet nature, he needs an experienced dog owner who can continue to help him blossom into the best possible version of himself and make sure he meets new people slowly to build his trust. Taking Piglet home will have to be a gradual process so we are looking for a special person that is open and willing to invest the time needed to get to know and understand him before transitioning to a new home. 

He walks great on leash and has does well with other dogs out on walks and in playgroup. 

Piglets quirks are also his most endearing qualities. In the words of the original Piglet, 'The things that make me different are the things that make me, me'!

If you are interested in meeting Piglet, email kat.sanders@lostdogrescue.org

Sponsored by Tucker and Ruby

animal.description: Cousin is the funniest, goofiest little guy you will ever meet. He is about 7 years old, but has not shed his puppy personality. He is 30 pounds, and his underbite is a full inch! He loves to swim, fetch, and play with toys and friends. He is very rambunctious at playtime, but is a big snuggler once he settles down. He is good with other dogs, but will only be adopted to a home with a larger dog, and no cats. He is friendly with small dogs and cats, but accidentally injured a small dog trying to play, so he should not be unattended with smaller animals. He loves kids, and would love a home with a large playful dog and a fenced yard. Adopt Cousin! You will never stop laughing!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.AdoptableBolt is rescued from a hoarding situation. He and his sister Star are playful but still a bit cautious of humans. But they allow us to touch both of them. Bolt is a fast boy and likes to sneak out behind you when opening and closing doors and gates. We think it is a game for him because he does not go anywhere. With training, Bolt will be an excellent companion for outdoor activities and snuggling on the couch. He likes to sleep in his crate. He gets along with all dogs and people.

All dogs and puppies are fully wormed, receive rabies and core vaccinations, microchipped, behavior assessed with other dogs and humans (sorry, no cat testing is done here), spend a minimum of 3 weeks free-ranging within a pack of 30 dogs to grow confidence and trust and may have DNA results. All dogs receive lifetime behavior support and can be returned anytime without a fee. 

PLEASE NOTE: You MUST complete an adoption application in order to see or adopt a dog from us. The completed adoption application ensures your 'spot' in order of adoption. Emailing/calling with questions will delay your adoption process.

Buddy is a playful young dog. He is very affectionate and really loves his humans. He has excellent recall and listens well. He sometimes will attempt to "punch" a dog away from his human. If you tell him No before he does it he breaks off and does not "punch". With more reinforcement, this behavior should wane.

He needs an experienced dog family since he is so active. He gets along with most all adult large dogs. He is NOT GOOD with small dogs, puppies or cats. We think he will do well with one other dog who is tolerant of his adolescent antics.

He will make a great companion for a family or single person. Please think about saving Buddy as he has been here almost a year now. He is a really good boy and is loved by all who meet him.

Note: He may (or may not) but most likely will, knock over small children.

He really likes his crate and laying on the couch and bed snuggling with his human.

animal.description:
Looking for a tiny spitfire to call your own?  
Eloise has made such amazing progress since the days of being shut down in the shelter. She is still nervous around new people. But, once she gets to know you, she loves to be loved on about as much as she loves other dogs. 

We recommend a home with a male dog, as she tends to really favor hanging out with larger male dogs.  At only 1 year old and 29lbs, we feel like she is going to be a great addition to a home with someone willing to be patient for a bit. She is incredibly playful and full of life. She just needs a little time to show it. 
Want to foster or adopt this gorgeous girl?  Visit CaneRossoRescue.org to apply.

Thanks for considering a Cane Rosso Rescue dog! 
We place dogs mostly in Texas but have adopted out a few out-of-state as well.
 
If you are interested in one of our dogs, please first complete our adoption application.
You can find it at https://www.canerossorescue.org/adoption-application . Her adoption fee is $300 plus tax. Our dogs are spayed or neutered, microchipped, vaccinated and heartworm tested and treated (if tested positive) before going to a new home. For more information, visit our website www.canerossorescue.org
or email us at rescue@canerosso.com.

I’m okay w/ other dogs but not really interested in finding a doggy friend.  Cats?  No thanks!  I REALLY want a PERSON to call my own!  If you’re in the market for the buddy of a lifetime then please, please consider me! 
Wanna meet me?  Contact my foster Mom, Diane, at dk1enzo@cox.net or 310.507.3341.

animal.description: Moira (formerly Karla) is a sweet fun loving girl that loves to be around her people. She finds the shelter to be stressful and because she is sensitive, she's ready to be anywhere else. Moira may do better wearing a harness, she tries to play magic tricks and Houdini herself out of regular collars! She knows basic commands and has pretty good house manners. Karla will need lots of patience when she first meets people, but once she trusts you she will roll over to allow lots of belly rubs! She gets anxious being left alone, so someone that is home a lot would be the best match for her. Moira would prefer to be the only dog to get all the attention in her new home. No apartments please. Chester is very athletic, smart,  and easy to train, so will do well with an adopter who is active and enjoys walks/hikes/exploring outdoors. animal.description: Chulo spent 2 months in the Wichita Animal Shelter. We inquired about the incident that led to his incarceration at the city shelter. Apparently he has gotten loose a few times and this time he scratched an older woman on the leg that led to him being impounded and deemed a potentially dangerous dog. His owner was unable to comply with the pen requirements due to landlord issues and could not reclaim . Sadly this is why Chulo has been kept locked up since August. We were never made aware of his situation until the emergency email October 12th when we were contacted that there was an injury to his tail that had just occurred and that he was aggressive with staff and would require a catch pole to remove from the kennel for vet care. We were sent a video from rescue coordinator and we did NOT see a dog that was described as aggressive with staff that couldn't be removed from a kennel. We saw a sweet boy that was happy to follow commands for a kind word or treat. As a result we were able to go rescue this boy and get the tail issue checked out. There were no issues with leashing him up. He was not reactive to any of the other dogs, people or animal control officers he passed by and sweet as could be with the vet staff too. The Dr examined the tail which did not bother him at all and determined that this was probably just an old injury that had healed a long time ago.....

animal.description:
Hello potential new family, my name is Blake! I'm a 2 year old male Australian Cattle Dog (blue heeler) mix and I weigh 60 pounds. True to my breed I am extremely loyal to my owners but wary of strangers at first so I'm a bit anxious and vocal when it comes to meeting new people. In order to improve my socialization skills I will need a strong leader who is willing to give me a lot of time, effort and patience. I could use some obedience training. I am a very strong dude and could use some work on leash manners. I am a HIGH energy pup so I need lots of exercise and I'm very smart and very treat motivated so I'm easy to train. I'm a great running partner - I go running with my foster mom and dad. They usually wear me out around 5 miles. I am potty trained and crate trained - I crate up easily when asked. I'm a little obsessed with car rides - they're kinda my favorite! I love running and playing with my furry foster siblings (all dogs - unknown with cats)! I've named myself captain of the "squirrel patrol" and enjoy chasing squirrels and watching them play in the backyard tree. I have not been observed around children, though once I've gotten to know and trust them I bet we'd be best friends! I can be easily excited into some hilarious zoomies. I'm a huge goofball and I keep my foster humans laughing constantly. If you start dancing I can't help but to join in - I'll even hold onto your hips with my paws. I give THE BEST hugs!! Most of all I enjoy being near my human and being loved on - I am so incredibly lovable and loyal. Finding a home with Australian cattle dog experience would be a plus, but obviously doesn't rule you out from being able to enjoy all the fun and love I have to offer! 
If you would like to meet me, fill out an application and the Bella staff will arrange it.

animal.description:
Note: Dogs are pack animals and do not do well away from other members of their pack. The adopter is the alpha member of the pack, and the dog or puppy needs as much one-on-one contact with the alpha as possible. For this reason, all Route 66 Rescue Inc. dogs are adopted to inside homes only. They must be on leash, or inside a secure fence when outside, and not left outside alone when no one is home. Invisible fencing does not qualify as protection since other animals and strangers have access to the dog. The dogs must be returned to Route 66 Rescue, Inc. if ever given up by the adopter. Thank you for understanding we want only the best for the dogs you give a forever home.

Sadie is a blonde and white mixed bred girl.  Her birthday is estimated to be around 11/03/2016, and on 11/03/2020, she weighed 43.6 lbs.  Sadie takes a while to get acquainted, and has the appearances of a dog that has not had good experiences with the people she has been around.  She hasn't learned to trust and will need a forever family who will take the time to show her what a loving family is.  She will be adopted to an adult forever family .
 
Please complete and return the adoption application to meet any of our adoptable dogs.
http://www.route66rescueinc.com/adoption-application.html Thank you for visiting our site. Please come back often.

animal.description:
Lucky Beagle!Kane was born around November 11, 2012 and weighs about 20 pounds. Kane was found roaming the streets of Buffalo and was picked up by a good samaritan who contacted both the local dog control officer and SPCA. When no one claimed Kane she brought him to JR as she was unable to afford the dental care that was needed. Kane arrived with a mouth full of infection, unaltered, and extremely skinny. After his neuter and dental, which resulted in 20 teeth needing to be pulled, Kane is like a shiny new penny and ready for a wonderful life! We want to mention that his teeth were SO bad that there may be more dental work needed in the not so distant future. Kane must have a fenced because his nose will get in him trouble. Kane rides well in the car and is fine with the other dogs, cats, and kids, and loves to snuggle! We have found that he is not going to do well in an apartment type setting as he does have that Beagle sound that real Beagle humans love! Also, maybe due to the dental disease that we are struggling to find what he wants to eat. He won't touch canned food which is very odd, but has been dining on hard boiled eggs, those cheap peanut butter and cheese crackers......Asian type noodles and hard dog biscuits......he is very confusing and we'll keep trying things. Update: Christmas 2020 seems to be no exception to bad news throughout the year. Kane is in liver failure and we are keeping him comfortable until it is time to let him go. We are very sad - he is SO sweet!!! The Adoption Fee for this dog is n/a
Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general our fees include spay/neuter, all age appropriate vaccines, Home Again micro-chipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES

We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption.

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

animal.description:
[PLEASE READ TILL THE END IF INTERESTED IN ADOPTING/MEETING THE PUP for instructions)

My name’s Rex. I have two short arms, am kinda scaly, and had a starring role in Spielberg’s Jurr- JUST KIDDING. I’m actually a 3 y/o, male, shepard pit/lab mix who tips the scales at a mean 60lbs. I was brought way of The Cantu Foundation when my owner left me behind after he moved out. Pretty rude, right? As you can probably gather, he wasn’t the best owner, so I’m only semi potty trained. Don’t worry though—I’m a quick study and make up for it in the leash department! I’m a big guy who doesn’t pull. Practically a dreamboat, right?
 
Before I got to my current comfy digs, I was found malnourished and covered in mange. I had been living on the streets and spent my days hunting for scraps while trying not to get hit by those dangerous people-movers (Think you call them cars?). Anyways, I’m a loyal guy who just wants to be emotionally tethered to a human. Specifically, a human who loves and cares about me. Because of my past, I’m still learning how to adjust to life in the burbs. Sometimes I let my anxiety get the best of me and lack the confidence needed to be a regular dog. But that’s where YOU come in! Just be kind and patient with me while I decompress and get acclimated. It won’t take long before I’ll feel confident that I’m safe!
 
So you may be asking yourself, ‘How does Rex do around other dogs?’ Well you asked the right pupper! I like small and large doggos even hyper ones, I know how to match their energy. Sometimes they get all up in your business and it can bug, okay? Cats, however, I’m not sure about. Never met one, but I loved the movie despite those Rotten Tomato reviews! Kids I do okay with, but older is better. I’d lump younger kids in the younger doggos category—all up in my business!
 
Now that you know what a catch I am, let’s talk about the areas where I can improve. I have a tad bit of separation anxiety. I was abandoned once, remember? My foster dad says it isn’t so bad though, because I make up for it in the lovable, snuggle-buddy, and people-pleasing categories. Since I’ve lived most of my life in streets, I still have yet to master the stairs but don’t worry I can walk up a flight of stairs on my own now! 
 
I would flourish in a home with another doggo friend, I will also do well in a home with small humans (7 years old and up) My paws are crossed that I end up with a family who will be patient and train me so I can be the best doggo this side of Mexico. My adoption fee is $400, which includes spaying/neutering and vetting care. If I sound like the dude for you OR WOULD LIKE TO SCHEDULE A MEET AND GREET , FILL OUT THE FORM ON THE WEBSITE! thecantufoundation.org/adopt

animal.description:
Hi I'm Jackson and I'm a year old, neutered male Cur Mix weighing about 45 lbs. 

I am a spunky guy who likes to enjoy life.  

I know my basic commands and am working on consistently doing as I’m told.  Sometimes I’m just so excited, I forget to do what’s said to me.  When I’m reminded, I can sit, come, stay like a champ.  I'm very food motivated so the snacky snacks help me to focus on what is expected of me.  

I go potty outside when I am kept on a schedule.  I don’t know how to show my foster family that I need to go out yet.  

I'm good with other dogs, kids, I’ve met a cat, and even live with hamsters! I watch them with curious puppy eyes but I do not try to get into their cage. 

I’m learning to keep four on the floor. But frankly, I really like people and sometimes my excitement gets the best of me so I jump to say hello. 

I have developed a comfort in my crate although I would much rather hang with the family.  Some snacky snacks in my crate make it a much happier place. 

I have fabulous new and improved leash walking skills! I’d love a family who is active to take me out and about to burn my energy and see the site of my new hometown which would give me opportunity to show off what a good boy I am when we go out. 

If you happen to need a fun loving playful guy to be your new BFF, I’m taking applications and just in time to be your Valentine!

If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website-?www.luckymuttsrescue.org?and submit an application. Our application process includes landlord approval and vet checks. Please make sure all of your information is current and accurate, including a valid email address and phone numbers. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and/or cancel your application. We strive to process all applications in a timely manner, but with the high volume of applications we are receiving, it is taking anywhere from 1-3 weeks.  You may be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions.  Once all of your information is reviewed and if your application is approved, you will be notified via email.  Submitting an application and receiving an approval does not guarantee you will be adopting the dog you applied for.  Once you move to the meet and greet process, you will be contacted by the foster family to further discuss the dog, and answer questions you may have, and if applicable, a meet and greet will be set up at our adoption center.   Meet and greets are only set up with approved applicants, and we require all members in the household to be present, as well as any current dogs in the home. 
Current Adoption Fees Are:$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
Bonded pairs vary
The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test, (if over 6  months) and a certified veterinary inspection. Please be aware, listed dog breeds are based on information provided and cannot be guaranteed.  Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen, we receive several applications for each dog. Our adopters are picked based on the needs of the dog, and the home we feel with best fit based on your responses to our application, vet information and landlord requirements.   Approved applicants not chosen for the dog you applied for, will be in active status for a period of six months.  We encourage you to watch Petfinder, Facebook and our website for upcoming dogs.  Should you see a dog that interests you,please send us a Facebook message or an email with your approval number.  Please be patient with us, as Lucky Mutts Rescue is run strictly by volunteers and many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thank you for considering Lucky Mutts Rescue for your next furry family member!

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Tater Salad, a handsome, smart, young (Est. DOB 10/27/2019) Boxer mix (about 35 lbs.).  I was rescued from a high-volume shelter where it was so stressful for me since I'm hearing impaired.  Now that I'm in foster care, it is so much better and I've been to doggy school and have learned hand signals - hey, I said I was smart!  I do well with dogs of all sizes, I'm even mellow around my bossy foster brother.  I'm good with kids old enough to understand my special needs.    I am quickly learning about being in a house and looking for that family that will continue with loving and gentle training to become the perfect gentleman.  I do well on a leash and hope long walks are in my future.  I'm friendly with people, love being with my person and playing with toys or sticks. animal.description: Meet Sally. This sweet, sweet girl was found short-chained to a tree, covered in ants, and emaciated. She had never known love in her 3 years of life, but instead was used for puppies. She was so very grateful to the volunteer that found her that day, and happily accepted the hose he had to use to wash the ants off of her poor painful body, and she melted right into his arms to be loaded into a vehicle and taken to safety. She had so many ant bites her hair had already fallen out in patches, and more would be lost before she could be healed. She was loaded with intestinal parasites, and of course heartworm positive. Butttt....look at his beautiful girl now. All of her beautiful coat has filled back in, she’s been treated for the Intestinal parasites, fully vaccinated, spayed, microchipped, and is currently on slow-kill treatment for her heartworms and is doing great. This amazing girl is so full of love for her people and other dogs, even though she has no reason to trust or love after the way she was neglected. She’s loving her life as a family member in her foster home, and she will crate, but she doesn’t like it too much. We can’t blame her since it represents a little of how she lived before she was rescued. Sally is a sweet and loving girl who is ready to find her very own family and live her happily ever after. And we can’t think of a single rescue that deserves it more than this amazing girl!!

animal.description:
Hey there, I'm Mojo! A spunky senior pup ready to take your breath away with my dashing good looks and festive holiday spirit. I'm a very sweet and lovable boy! I was rescued with my mom (Chewie) and my 4 siblings (Pudgy, Tater, Twoie, and Tiri), and we are all up for adoption. I can be adopted by myself or into a house with another dog. Or, if you are looking to add multiple dogs to your home, I can be adopted with another pup in my family (the more the merrier, right?). My brother Tater is the silliest one of the bunch, but I take second place I think - I love to do the 'downward dog' stretch and prance around in my adorable sweaters. You would never know I'm a senior - I'm not high energy but I still have pep in my step. I enjoy a leisurely walk around the neighborhood, hanging out with other dogs, and then heading in to cuddle up in my bed for a nap. I love peanut butter Kongs and trying any new treat - I take them gently from your hand too. I'm easygoing, friendly with people and dogs, and, like my name Mojo suggests, am just a really cool dog. I cannot wait to find my forever home, so ask ARNO about meeting me today!

animal.description:
Bootsie

 

SPECIAL NEEDS

Bootsie does not have usage of her backend.  She requires bladder and bowel expressions throughout the day, and she is not able to use her back legs.  There does. not appear to be any pain or discomfort.

 

DESCRIPTION (BIO)

Bootsie is a spunky Dachshund who is only 4 years young.  She is fun and lively; full of confidence and pizazz!  Bootsie does not have usage of her back legs, but it truly does not slow her down.  As soon as Bootsie was fitted with a wheelchair, she has been on the go!  The exercise is also helping her drop some pounds.  Once she gets down to her 11-pound goal, there may be no stopping her.  Bootsie loves special attention…and she’ll demand it if desired. 

 

The ideal home for Bootsie would be one level since stairs will pose a danger.  Bootsie requires bladder and bowel expressions.  She’ll thrive with someone who understands her physical limitations yet sees Bootsie’s limitless capacity to love and entertain.  This lady is an Olympic snuggler.  Show her some love, and you’ll have a shadow and buddy for life.

 

Adopters must live in the Los Angeles area.

animal.description:
Greta
Breed: Pitbull mix
DOB: 10/01/2019
Gender: Female
Adoption fee: $175
Greta is a sweet girl with a quiet nature. It takes Greta a few minutes to warm up to new people but once she accepts you she's a friend for life. She is going to make a devoted companion for a calm loving family. Greta enjoys the company of other dogs and children. Greta's ideal new home will be willing to help her with house-training and socialize her with people. With a little help Greta will be the most well behaved dog around!!! If you would like to meet Greta, please fill out an adoption application today!!!Please read the animal bios completely before requesting additional information as we do our best to answer the most frequently ask questions in these bios. 

In order to adopt one of our animals an application must be submitted and approved. You can find these applications by going to http://humanemorgan.org/index.php?page=adoption 

ABOUT ADOPTING FROM THE HSMC: 
The shelter address is 1170 Fairground Rd. Madison, GA 30650. For more information on any of our pets, please feel free to email us at INFO@HUMANEMORGAN.ORG give us a call at 706-343-9977. 
All dogs are heartworm negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
All cats are FeLv/FIV negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
We are open 10am-5pm Monday-Saturday, we schedule our last adoption at 4pm everyday to allow our staff enough time to feed and walk dogs. 
We are an animal shelter and therefore are not able to individually potty train our residents. Many adult dogs do arrive ""house broken"" however due to animal behavior any change in environment will make an emotional impact on the animals and therefore initiate unwanted behaviors during the acclamation period. Please keep this in mind. Puppies do not have the biological maturity to maintain absolute bladder or bowel control and will require a certain degree of potty training and house breaking. Please consider the time and commitment it takes to provide the necessary building blocks for these special babies, prior to submitting your application. 
If you have any questions please email us at info@humanemorgan.org and provide name of the animal you are interested in, in the subject line. 
Thank you, HSMC Staff 

ADOPTION FEES Adoption Fees may change without notice. Always verify the fee when finalizing the adoption. 
~ Cats and Kittens ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $100 
* 1-5 Years = $75 
* Over 5 Years = $50 
** Purebred cats and kittens may be subject to special pricing 

~ Mix Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $200 
* 1 -3 Years = $175 
* 4-8 Years = $150 
* Over 8 Years = $100

~ Purebred and Designer Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $375 
* 1-3 Years = $350 
* 4-8 Years = $275 
* Over 8 Years = $150 

~ Medical and Special Needs ~ 
We have rescued dogs and cats which require additional medical care or that have special needs which are not life threatening. In these cases we may require a higher fee to help recoup the costs of their care while at our rescue.

If you are looking for an affectionate best friend who loves to snuggle, look no further! Even though Woody likes to be active, he is happy to snooze until you are ready to start the day, and is always happy to snuffle up for a solid nap. He's loving, silly, outgoing and absolutely ready to find his forever home! Come meet Woody today!

animal.description:
Ohhh Papa Elf What a cute boy and yet not ONE inquiry He sits and waits for the phone to ring but all he hears is silence We dont understand why! Is it because hes 8? Eight is a great age! Still lively and fun loving yet also lives to relax! Papa was pulled from @nycacc right at the start of Covid. Pops is about 60 pounds so a medium size and he currently is lucky to be in a Foster home 

Papa Elf is ok on leash, he does get happily excited when he sees people so he may jump up to greet you, but his foster peeps are working on that. Once he knows hes safe, hes loving and he has lots of energy to play. He sleeps in his crate like a good boy and his favorite toy is a ducky!! He adores rolling around in the grass and listens to commands. 

Papa gets along with other dogs and a proper intro is mandatory to be set up for success! Hes not a fan of kitties (his loss lol). Mr. Elf will do best in a home that is consistent with rules - he thrives with a strong leader. Hes neutered, up to date on vaccines and housebroken. He is doing so wonderful with all the structure he now has!! 

Why oh why is this boy still homeless? He matters just like they all do. Do you have a space in your home and heart to make his dreams come true? 
If you would like to hear more about Papa Elf DM or apply at www.puppykittynyc.org 

 @williamjamesmedia

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Thank you for your interest in adopting one of our foster animals! The first step in the adoption process is submitting an application. Please visit our website for more information and a link to the application: www.kgarl.org/info/adoption
Adoption process

Once your application is received, the application process begins. We will review your application, check your references, check with your vet (if there are other animals in the household), speak to a landlord (if you rent), and arrange for a home visit.

Submitting an application does not guarantee a specific dog or cat. We strive to match the personality and needs of our foster dogs and cats to a family who will best fulfill those needs. If a family is not approved for a particular pet, it does not mean they will not be a good pet owner, it just means that their needs and the needs of the particular pet don't match. We do not adopt on a "first come, first serve" basis.

Please note that we do not do same day adoptions. If you are applying for a popular animal (such as puppies, small dogs, or special breeds), it can take several days for our volunteers to reach a decision that is best for the animal. We understand that it's difficult to wait, but please don't email us multiple times a day to check on the status of your application. We are a very small group and the same people that are reviewing your application are also replying to hundreds of emails and facebook messages. We are all volunteers and have full time jobs outside of KGARL, so any time spent replying to emails/messages is time we are not reviewing your application.

Once your application is pre-approved (meaning, we don't see any red flags based on our preliminary review of your application), the applicant may be invited to meet their potential family member at a location convenient to the foster family (usually at the King George Petco). Adoptions will NOT take place at the meet & greet, this is just a chance for us to get to know you and for you to spend time with our animals. After the meet and greet, we will ask that you spend some time thinking over your decision and we will do the same.

After the application review process is complete (meet & greet with animal, home visit, reference/vet checks, background check, etc.), if all is acceptable to both adopter and KGARL and we all agree to move forward, we will schedule a day/time to finalize the adoption. The adopter will be asked to sign the final paperwork and we will collect the adoption fee (cash, check, or paypal are all acceptable). At this time, you can either pick up your pet, or schedule a time to do so. Adopters will be required to schedule an appointment with their veterinarian of choice within 10 days of taking your new pet home.

All Adoptions Include:

Lifetime of free advice from KGARL!

Spayed or Neutered Pet

Heartworm, FIV, Feline Leukemia Testing

Complete medical records

Up to date on core vaccines

On Flea/Tick Preventative

Microchipped

Sample of Pet Food

Adoption Fees (unless otherwise noted in the pet's description):

Special Breeds of Dogs: See pet's description
Puppies: $400
Adult Dogs : $350
Adult Hounds and Beagles: $250
Kittens: $125
Adult Cats: $100

animal.description:
As 2020 is behind us we all have lots to be thankful for. And for our shelter one would be the incredible improvement in 2 sibling German Shepherds Boone and Zena(now adopted).  They lived their first 3 years in such a difficult situation. And they came to us "skin and bones" with little fur. It has taken a few months but these sweet pups are now beginning to enjoy life! After some quality food, medicated baths, lots of socialization, and loving TLC from our great volunteers. Boone is very treat motivated, is so happy to see us, and has a bark as deep as a baritone singer. He will continue to need more socialization and positive training. He would do best in a home without kitties or young children. We can't wait to find that very special loving forever families for Boone! His DOB is 7/23/17.

Dog adoption fee is $259. This includes the spay or neuter surgery, age appropriate current vaccines, microchip, and preventative flea treatment.

For any questions regarding the application process or a specific dog or cat please email info@sunnyskysshelter.org. If you have not received a reply in 48 hours please verify your email address. Emailed questions are typically answered within 24 hours.

Thank you for your interest in one of our rescue pets. During this unprecedented time we venture into the unknown together and we thank you for your understanding and patience during this process. Together we are working toward the same goal of providing forever homes for all our furry friends.

animal.description:
Buddy is a sweet old guy that we just could not say no to. This poor senior, estimated to be about 11 years old, was part of a cruelty case. He was confiscated with several others so you know it was horrible.

The others were a little bit younger, a little bit cuter, but nobody could have been sweeter. So though everyone else got safe a little earlier, Buddy is now, and forever will be safe!

He is said to be a ridgeback/hound mix, 11 years old, heartworm positive but otherwise healthy. He enjoys a nice walk and likes other dogs.

Buddy spent over a month at Barc, after a lifetime of neglect.Boarding is going to seem like paradise to this boy but let's get him to a real home, foster or adoptive, fast so he can enjoy every minute!

animal.description:
A young female Weimaraner in our rescue program recently whelped a litter of puppies that came from a breeding with a purebred German Shepherd. 

There are two male puppies and all are healthy and thriving. Together with their mother, these puppies are fostered in a calm and caring foster home in Scottsdale, AZ. 

We are looking for adoptive families who preferably have experience with the Weimaraner and/or German Shepherd breeds, and who have the flexibility and plenty of time to raise their puppy and be with him or her both during weekdays and on weekends . 
Specifically, we are looking for families who are home most of the time, and whose lives are centered around their pets, as this is what is preferred by most members of the Weimaraner breed.

A structured program of learning obedience and socialization will be required from adopters. The puppies are ready to go to their adoptive homes immediately. 

If you are interested in one of these puppies and would like more information before submitting an application for adoption, PLEASE EMAIL us at contact@weimaranerrescue.org .
Please do not send an interest through Petfinder, email us directly at the address listed above. 
When emailing us please tell us more about yourselves, your family, your lifestyle, and what you are looking for in an adoptive dog. 
We receive so many generic inquiries each day, so please feel free to share information. 
We are a transparent organization and are happy to share equally with you.

Thank you!

animal.description:
The New & Improved Marvelous Max -- Coming soon!
 


MAX!! 
 


If this handsome guy's face looks familiar, you're not mistaken. Max has been with HHS for quite a bit while we figured out some of his behavioral stuff. Max can be reactive around other dogs and due to his large size, his reaction can be pretty scary to some folks. We know Max just doesn't know the proper way to say "hi" to his fellow canines and with a little help, he'd be the perfect pup. So, with the help of Breakthrough K9's training experts and their intensive reactive dog training regimen, Max is now well on his way to learning the world isn't such a scary place! 
 


Like most rotties, Max is an absolute goofball at heart. He loves nothing more than curling up to watch some TV with his person. He likes to mosey outside once in awhile to sniff around, but he's a true lazybones when it comes down to it. He loves cuddling with his stuffies and is perfectly crate trained (he loves to sleep there!) and potty trained. 
 


Max will need an owner who is confident and has dealt with reactive dogs before. The owner must also agree to attend training sessions, at no cost, with Max at Breakthrough K9 in Mechanicsville, VA, so they can learn all of the skills and techniques needed to keep Max calm, cool, and collected when faced with day-to-day stressors. 
 


We are so excited to see the new and improved Max once he's graduated from his training. We're sure Max is bound to find his forever home very soon! 
 


If you are interested in adopting Max, please fill out an application at www.henricohumane.org/adopt-a-dog

animal.description:
Mikey was born 12/5/2019 in a foster home in Georgia. He was adopted at 8 weeks old by a family in Georgia, who moved to Orlando, FL in February. At that time, they decided Mikey could no longer be a part of their family (he didn't seem to like their two children) and instead of giving the dog back to the rescue (WE REQUIRE YOU RETURN MIKEY TO US IF YOU EVER HAVE TO REHOME HIM) she gave him away to what she thought would be a good home. The man seemed very nice, but shortly after taking Mikey, he lost his job to COVID-19 and gave the dog to his mother, who let Mikey go.

Mikey was run over by a car in late September. Hillsborough County Pet Resource Center ended up with him and when no dog rescues stepped up, a cat rescue did, so they wouldn't euthanize him. 

His vet bills were over $3,000 and we're still getting him healthy enough to be adopted. He had punctures in his lungs, was missing a lot of skin, and is now terrified of walking by roads with cars (but he loves to ride in cars!). 

He LOVES to sit on the couch and in your lap. He loves to sleep in the bed with you. VERY friendly. VERY affectionate. He just needs time to get to know you. He LOVES his foster mommy now!! He'll be the best dog ever.

He loves his foster brothers, a 80lb Shepherd mix and a 70lb Shepherd mix.  Mikey will be about 65-70lbs at his ideal weight, but he is not a tall dog and can't counter surf. He will need stairs to get on and off of the couch and bed. He can jump up, but he shouldn't be. Allowing him to jump when he's young will make life harder on him when he's older.

It's likely he'll need special care when he gets into his 8 or 9 years of age. If you can't afford to care for him (a possible wheelchair when he's older, possible arthritis) when he's older DO NOT ADOPT HIM. He is a part of the family, not a decoration!

If you can't afford him, you can't adopt him.

His adoption fee is $300. He is neutered, vaccinated, heartworm free, flea free, and ready for adoption in November to the BEST HOME out there. We will be very picky, we don't want him abandoned again. 

No children under the age of 13. No small dogs, he likes to romp and doesn't know how big he is. No elderly people in the home, as he jumps when he's excited and will easily knock down a child or an older person and potentially hurt them.

You CANNOT LIVE NEAR A BUSY ROAD and you must OWN YOUR OWN HOME to adopt Mikey. We will be doing a home check, and every member of the family must meet MIkey.

animal.description:
FOSTERS OR ADOPTERS NEEDED ASAP!!

These sweet girls are Missy and Maggie. They are sweet older Chi girls who are believed to be  around 8 years old. They are chunky girls at 17 lbs (Missy) and 14lbs (Maggie). Sadly, they lost their owner to Covid recently and now these girls are in need of a new home ASAP!! They were their owners entire world and were very spoiled. These girls are not bonded. So they can go to foster or adoptive homes together or separate. They are a little timid at first but don’t have any aggression. If you go a little slow they open up within minutes. They truly are sweet little lap babies who need a new lap to call their own. If you can help either temporary or forever with one or both of these girls, please fill out an app below. They will be fully utd and altered before placement!

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

ADOPTION APPLICATION

animal.description:
Female, 5 years, pit bull X, 70 lbs

Siara was very timid and scared when she arrived in her foster home but is slowly coming around.  She has taken quite a bit of time to get used to living in a house and she does spook with loud noises.  She has not been around cats yet, but her foster thinks she would be best in a home without them, as she does have a prey drive towards other small animals.  She is good with other dogs and has not been around small children yet.  She is a quiet dog and rarely ever barks.  She is still working on her housetraining, but having been in rescue her whole life, this may take some more time.  She is scared of being in the car and also not used to being on a leash.  She hasn’t had interest in toys yet.  Overall, this quiet girl is still getting used to her new circumstances and it may take some more time for her to realize that she is safe and cared for.  She is looking for a new home who will take their time with her and allow her to come out of her shell in her own time.

Our rescue is called BARCS. We are a registered Non Profit.
Our Website is www.barcsrescue.com. All our animals are posted on the website and updated often. If you would like to proceed we need an adoption application to be filled out. They can be found on our website. Once we receive your application, we will contact you to arrange a meeting with the pup you are interested in. 
We look forward to hearing from you

animal.description:
Piksi arrived to the U.S. from Iran on November 10th. They literally took his crate off the plane and loaded it in the back of my car. He was in transport and in the crate for 36 hours! The woman who assisted with the transport told me that Piksi had been found on the street in Iran when he was approximately 6-8 weeks old. His ears had been cut off and were still bleeding when they found him. He was taken to a shelter where he stayed in a kennel indoors for the next 10 months of his life. When he finally came out of the crate in my back yard, it was the first time he had ever walked on grass. I have since renamed him Jupiter, and he does answer to that name. (He's much too large to be a Piksi, and he didn't recognize that name anyway!) He is a very large dog, he weighs approximately 80 lbs. He has a beautiful, thick, and very soft tawny coat with black points. He is a gorgeous dog! He did not have the advantage of any training or socialization or even kindness for the first year of his life. He was terrified of everything when he first arrived - leashes, cars, noises, etc. He has made tremendous progress. But he is still trying to figure out the world around him. He lacks confidence, and cannot determine who is friend or foe. He is very wary of other dogs and men. We are currently working with a trainer to build his confidence. He would do well with a strong owner who can give him boundaries, which make him feel safer. He is relaxed here in his foster home, and even has a canine buddy that he loves to play with. When he feels safe and relaxed, he is a real sweetheart! Unfortunately, he still sees lots of danger in the world and most situations make him very uncomfortable, but we're working on that. Because of his size and fearfulness, he will need a home with no young children (under 15) or other pets. And he will need to continue his training and have boundaries set for him. He does much better in quiet environments, where there isn't a lot of commotion. With patience, consistent boundaries, and training, he can grow into a loyal, relaxed companion.Accuracy is not guaranteed; however, information provided is accurate to the best of our knowledge.

For more information on the pet, please send an email to info@aforeverhome.org
