animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Are you looking for a couch potato? Well, swipe left 'cause that ain't Margarita, or Rita or RiRi for short. She's the epitome of a shepherd. She thinks that ball is life, thrives on training and structure and is super smart (and a little naughty). She is looking for a leader in her life, a partner, adventure buddy and a best friend. She'll give you 1000% and she is looking for someone that will give the same back to her. Is that you?

Rita is awesome. She's quiet in her crate and will have the most bizarre sleeping positions. She brings the ball right to your feet and sits for the next throw (and it better be a looong one!). Stuffy toys were meant to be deconstructed. She is beyond super smart and picks up what you want her to do right away. She's also a velcro dog so get ready to always have company no matter what you do. She is a champion snuggler and there is nothing better after a good play time than snuggles and kisses on the couch or being a bed hog. She loves pets and kisses and will be very insistent that you give her love. She rides like a champ in the car. She takes treats oh, so gently and has the softest cuddliest fur around. I can't stop kissing her gorgeous face. She will bury her head in your lap for cuddles and ear rubs. And she makes me laugh every day with her goofy face and sweet nature. Of course, Rita will push your buttons a few times to make sure you mean that she really, really can't pull that toy out of the trash. I mean, she worked really hard on it. Typical teenager stuff.

Like all of us, she's working on being her best doggie self. She gets too excited and will jump for the ball out of your hand but just needs to be reminded that good girls sit for a ball throw. She's working on her leash skills, especially when there are distractions around. She's lived with 10 dogs before but forgets to be cool in meeting new dogs and her over the top energy might not make her a favorite with some dogs. We have been working on her leash skills and she has made tremendous progress. We visit Home Depot and pet stores to work on her leash skills and being cool around lots of people, dogs and noise. She honestly can do anything as long as you have a tennis ball around as a reward and is one of the smartest dogs I've ever met.

If you are looking for a dog that will truly be a partner in your life, that will be active with you and where the two of you will grow a deep and meaningful relationship, then she's the one for you. Are you the one for her?

Basics: Female, 55#, active, HW-, spayed and located near Martinsburg WV. Check out more pictures and video on Instagram @maechangyoungIf you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

animal.description:
I am Groot!

Little blind Groot was found as a stray. He had no microchip, was very matted, and couldn't walk when he got to Orange County Shelter! He is approximately 10 years old and weighs 20 lbs. When Groot arrived at Frosted Faces he could walk, but was very stiff. Following an examination and X-rays by our vet, we learned Groot has IVDD (Intervertebral Disk Disease).

He has been receiving acupuncture weekly at Frosted Faces, and it's been helping him! He now can go for short walks and really enjoys himself, as you can see in the cute video included with Groot's photos.

Groot has been on an extended Frosted Fling. His Fling Mom decided to extend it, because she noticed Groot's mobility improving, and his cute personality blossoming! She reports Groot is potty trained and gives a little bark when he needs to go out. He holds it through the night as he sleepw on a dog bed.

There are four other dogs in Groot's Fling home, and he gets along very well with them!

He's a great work-from-home buddy, laying at his Fling Mom's feet and rubbing against her legs when it's time to take a break and give hime some cuddles! Groot especially loves when his Fling Mom holds him like a baby. His legs have grown stronger from going on several short walks daily, and he really enjoys them. Groot loves being outside in the warm sunshine. He's such a sweet boy, and he asks for so little.

Groot's

wish for 2021 is to find a Forever Family. Might that be you? Apply at:
www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 1/31/21 KG

animal.description:
Looks like: Chihuahua Mix
Female, 3 years old, 12 pounds

Tosh greets every day with spunk and enthusiasm and pays little attention to her funny gait. History of scoliosis? Not if you ask her! While she is a little uncoordinated due to this medical history, she doesn't let that stop her. She walks well on a leash, but does use a lot of energy when she walks so prefers them to be on the shorter side. But don't worry, she'll be sure to let you know when she gets tired. 

Tosh gets along well with other dogs and is a social butterfly who loves being around people. She loves squeaker toys and ADORES treats. She loves snuggles and gives lots of kisses. She is a fairly quiet gal, but does bark to show how excited and happy she is when her person returns home. She does well in the car, sleeps through the night, and is great in the home. 

Tosh would do best in a house with no stairs, as her condition means she needs to avoid stairs completely or be carried up and down them. Additionally, she would do best in a house that has carpeting or rugs to help her move around more easily. Her desire to be around people means she'd also do best in a house with a person who is around a lot to give her the love she deserves - and she'll give it right back! 

Tosh came to POMDR from Santa Cruz County Animal Shelter and is ready to make her next transition into her forever home!

animal.description:
There's no place like home for the holidays, and nobody's wishing for a home more than sweet Sage. 
Meet SAGE. 3 years young, 45 lb shepherd mix who is READY to go home. Sage loves to be out in the yard, and she can jump 5 feet in the air- No joke! If you're looking for an AGILITY star, Sage is your gal! If you like to adventure on long walks in the woods, or run on the levee in the early mornings, Sage is your gal! If you are a couch potato, or leave your dog home alone for long periods of time, Sage is probably not a good match for you. We are looking for someone that will be willing to work with Sage and channel her energy in constructive ways. We think that once she's in a home that will set appropriate boundaries, keep her senses engaged, and provide consistency, that Sage will settle into the perfect dog. Sage is affectionate, super, DUPER happy, and adores people. She’s a great size too- not too big, and not too small. She’s beautiful, and she is food motivated, which can be helpful for training. Sage is not appreciative of other dogs or cats, and so she will need to be your one and only.  As mentioned, Sage can jump impressively high; this is something to take into consideration if you have young children. As it is, she can easily jump up to kiss grownups on the face with no problems! Sage is heart worm positive and will be treated at no cost to her adopter. Sage is available for rescue, foster or adoption at the JPAS West Bank location.  Call 504 349-5111 or email RYeaton@jeffparish.net for more info. 

Adoption fee includes vaccinations, spay/neuter, heartworm test, and microchip.

animal.description:
Mr. Clean is the sweetest soul to snuggle up with, he loves hard and aims to please his people. He absolutely loves belly rubs and to give as many kisses as you'll allow. His favorite thing is to stretch out on his belly and army crawl around the house - It's never fails to make his foster parents laugh hysterically. His house manners are immaculate - kennel trained, house trained, non-destructive and can free roam when you're gone without issue. Mr. Clean is a special boy with particular behavioral needs - he is looking for an adopter with plenty of time to dedicate to his behavioral needs and continue his training. He is a highly active boy who does not care for the couch potato lifestyle. He is an insanely smart, highly motivated dog. He aims to please his people and quickly learns new skills. His excitement/engagement when training with his foster mom is beyond impressive - he is just happy to be involved with whatever his human is doing. If you're looking for a loyal, active companion who will help you grow as a dog owner, Mr. Clean is your guy. Mr. Clean will need a home without any children under 16 and no other pets. 
Please email foster@kcpetproject.org for more information. Thank you!

animal.description:
*Special Needs* (Sorry about the novel... believe it or not this IS the 'short version'!)
Heads up... cutest dog ever coming through! Hi friends! My name is Ronan and I am about 2-3 years old. I have a secret special power that makes everyone I meet fall in love with me. 'Ridiculously charming' would be a great description of me! I seem to have endless energy but also endless snuggles & love. I am a very special guy looking for a very special home. 
I am a bit 'too much' for other pets and children, so I am looking for a home where I can be an only child. The 'parent(s)' I'm looking for is a very specific kind of person. Not only do I need to be an only child, I also have a medical condition that will make most people (understandably) not want to adopt me. 
As you can see in the photos... I'm kind of... um... naked. I originally came from a shelter in Texas where I was treated for demodex mange. They thought my fur should grow back fine, so they sent me on my way here to Wisconsin to find my forever family. I've been here at DCHS since July, and DCHS has been working with numerous vets to try to figure out my skin issues and why I remain naked. When the special medications, topical sprays, special shampoos & special diet didn't clear things up... I saw a dermatologist. After some biopsies, the results show I have skin cancer. Unfortunately, the cancer is too widespread on my skin to be treated, so my time on this earth is limited. 
I don't know that I am 'sick'... all I know is how badly I want a home of my own. I will need to continue to get weekly baths, and remain on the pain medication for the remainder of my life. How long will I live? No one has an answer for that. 
My quality of life needs to be closely monitored. I will likely require regular vet visits as I may be more prone to skin infections, and may also need x-rays to check if the cancer is spreading. 
I realize I'm not a highly adoptable dog, and that I come with some substantial 'issues'. I also realize I have a lot of love to give and will be an amazing companion to some lucky person(s)! 

(A message from DCHS: Ronan is absolutely correct that he is special, makes everyone fall in love with him, and will be a wonderful companion. He is a very loveable lug and we are 100% dedicated on finding him the right home. At this time, he is not suffering and he is not in need of humane euthanasia. He has life left to live, and wants to spend his days/weeks/months/years in a home... maybe yours? If you are interested in Ronan or have any questions, please feel free to e-mail jwagner@dunncountyhumanesociety.org)

Placement Recommendations:
Owner Experience Level: Some Experience
Cats: No Thank You
Dogs: No Thank You
Kids: Middle School +Want to know more? Please call us! We've found that back and forth via email regarding a specific animal is not always effective and quick because our email is not monitored on a regular basis. So, for specific information regarding this wonderful pet, please contact one of our adoption counselors at (715) 232-9790. They are available between the hours of 8 am and 7 pm (7 days a week, excluding holidays). Thanks for your interest!

animal.description:
***Please read before contacting us***

Donna is the sweetest girl ever!  Like most Frenchies, she has had some health challenges.  She has allergies, which seem to much better since changing her diet to grain free food.  She came to us with such a bad ear infection, her ear looked like cauliflower.  She had to put under anesthesia to clean it out.  She later got two corneal ulcers, which were also attributed to her itchy eyes from allergies.  She has come so far on the grain free diet she is on and I think will continue to get better.  Donna has been through a lot.  She loved the children and her family, but she was being attacked by an older dog in the house and was given up after she was attacked so aggressively she had her head shaved and two puncture wounds when we got her.  Despite her hardships, she is the most loving dog I have ever fostered.  I would keep her if I did not already have two dogs and I know she would be happiest without the competition of other dogs.  I am going to be very picky about the home she goes to because she deserves and needs forever.  

Donna likes short walks, the dog beach or just laying on the couch.  She is obsessed with tennis balls.  

Please contact us if you have any questions and can provide a home where she can get the care for her allergies she will need.  

Email mylittletoybreed@yahoo.com

animal.description: Hi everyone! My name is Astro. I am a Siberian Husky, who loves to cuddle. I am a very smart and fast learner. My favorite game is to search for treats that are hidden under cups or in another room. I take a little time to feel comfortable with new people but games and short walks are a fun way to bond with me. I have SO MANY good qualities- I am loyal, very affectionate, house trained, crate trained, well behaved on car rides, walk great on the leash (even when other nearby dogs bark at me!), and I know how to "shake" (you can teach me more fun tricks!). My ideal home would be a calm home with an experienced dog owner (no young kids for me since I get nervous with new people and I'd love to live as an only dog or with another calm dog)- I am currently on activity restriction due to being heartworm positive. 2020 has been quite a year for all of us - including me- I got rescued- yay, but had some medical issues to work out before I could be available for adoption. I'm ready now, but I'm still waiting to find my perfect match- maybe we could meet and make this crazy year have a good ending? Until then, stay safe y'all!

animal.description:
Dolly is a 2 year old, spayed female pointer mix. She weighs about 60 pounds. Dolly loves everyone she meets, adults, kids and dogs. Dolly is very sweet and loves to be close to her people. Dolly is well behaved and listens well, but could use some work on counter surfing and jumping. Dolly is a medium to high energy dog that needs an outlet for her energy. She loves other dogs and would love a dog playmate to run with her. A fenced yard would be ideal as she loves to run and would love a playmate to chase her, she’s very fast so they may never catch her. If she were to be an only dog she would need an owner dedicated to walking her, hiking with her or taking her for a run. Toys are very exciting for her and she plays nicely by herself. Dolly is a very sweet dog and will cuddle with you once she’s had her playtime or walk. Dolly is crate trained and has been consistent with going potty outside.

If you would like to be considered as an adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website- www.luckymuttsrescue.org and submit an application. Our process includes landlord approval and vet checks. We try to get applications processed in a timely fashion. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and possibly cancel your application from being processed, so please make sure that you include valid information and contact information. You will be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions. Once your application has been processed, you may be contacted by one of our volunteers to set up a home visit interview. After your home visit interview is completed, all of your information is reviewed. If your application is approved, you will be notified. Meet and greets with dogs are only set up with approved applicants, so if you want to meet a dog, it is vital that your home visit is completed and that your application is approved. Adoption fees generally are: 
$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test and prevention (if old enough) and veterinary inspection certificate. Breeds of dogs are best guesses and we don't guarantee any breed. Adopters are chosen by what situation will be best for the dog. Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen to adopt that dog. Lucky Mutts strives to match dogs to the best home and will work with your family to find a good match. Please remember that we are an organization that is completely run by volunteers, so please be patient as many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thanks for wanting to adopt!

animal.description:
Belle is the sweetest girl you will ever meet! She is 11 years young and is a Pit bull Terrier mix and she weighs just over 60 pounds. Meeting Belle you would never know her age by the way she acts as she has the health and activity level of a dog half her age!
Belle was brought to us with severe skin irritation and inflammation, overgrown nails, ear infection, severe snorting through her nose/mouth and all of her teeth have been chewed down to the nubs. We had her seen by our Vet ASAP and was prescribed some meds for her skin and ears and is feeling so much better! She has finished all her medication, her nails have been trimmed and her snorting is mostly coming from her throat but there is nothing concerning or that can be done for it as she has an elongated soft pallet which just makes her breathing louder than the average dog. It is very important that she doesn't become overweight so as to not put excessive strain on her breathing. Even though she doesn't have much for length of teeth she still eats dry kibble just fine as long as its a smaller kibble and most senior dog food is. 
Belle loves everyone she meets and thinks she is a lapdog! She loves to go for walks and following people around for pets and back scratches! Belle also loves to go for car rides and will hop right up into your vehicle!
We have not had the opportunity to test Belle with other dogs or cats but can certainly do that if a prospective home needs us to. We believe that Belle would do well with children 10 and up but not younger as she has no idea what personal space is and may try to sit on a smaller child's lap and accidently hurt them.
If you would like to set up a time to meet Belle please give us a call at 641-774-5113 as we are open by appointment only. 

If you would like to donate towards Belle's care please go to the top of this page and click on the Sponsor button. You will then be redirected to her Petfinder Sponsor/Donation page. Any amount is greatly appreciated!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

PLEASE NOTE: GPMR communicates primarily by email. If you have any questions regarding one of our Mastiffs, please read their bio and if you still have questions- drop us an email at info@greatplainsmastiffrescue.org . If you have questions about our adoption procedures, please go to our Pages of Interest on the left hand column under 'Adoption Info.' We answer email inquiries almost immediately-usually always within a few hours and phone calls are returned with 24-36 hours.

GPMR does not have a shelter. All of our dogs are kept in loving foster homes. We must have a completed adoption
application on file before meeting any of our mastiffs.

GPMR adopts to the states of Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas, Arkansas, Missouri, Louisiana and parts of Colorado.
!!!Any mastiffs being adopted out of the state of Oklahoma require a health certificate to be paid for by the adopter!!!

Meet Teddy! This sweet boy was found wandering in rural Texas and rescued by a good Samaritan who reached out to GPMR to take him in. We took him to the vet and guess what - he was microchipped! His owners had gone through a divorce several years ago and rehomed him with a family member and they thought Teddy was still there, so we're not sure what happened. Neither was in a position to take care of Teddy's extensive medical needs so Teddy came into GPMR. We also learned that he is 12 years old!!!!Teddy is in rough shape. He is emaciated, had fleas and intestinal parasites and tested positive for heartworms. His ears are so infected the canals are practically swollen shut. He has 2 large tumors on his anus, one the size of a grape and the other the size of a tennis ball which was ulcerated. Teddy also has some dental disease, eyelid issues and arthritis. He weighed 106 at his first visit when he should closer to 150-160 lbs.Despite being in very bad shape, Teddy has an amazing personality. He seems happy and is eating great. We ran labwork which was mostly normal, and after consulting with the vet we decided to proceed with a surgery. The vet removed the largest anal mass as it was partially covering the anus. They also flushed out his ears and started treatment for his infections.Recovery has been a little hard on this old man and has thrown his appetite off, so our focus right now is getting him eating regularly and put on some much needed weight. Once he's a healthy weight he will be seeking a forever home for Teddy. He does have arthritis like most Mastiffs his age.Teddy is being fostered in DFW area, TXSave a Mastiff...Adopt, Foster, Volunteer!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

PLEASE NOTE: GPMR communicates primarily by email. If you have any questions regarding one of our Mastiffs, please read their bio and if you still have questions- drop us an email at info@greatplainsmastiffrescue.org . If you have questions about our adoption procedures, please go to our Pages of Interest on the left hand column under 'Adoption Info.' We answer email inquiries almost immediately-usually always within a few hours and phone calls are returned with 24-36 hours.

GPMR does not have a shelter. All of our dogs are kept in loving foster homes. We must have a completed adoption
application on file before meeting any of our mastiffs.

GPMR adopts to the states of Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas, Arkansas, Missouri, Louisiana and parts of Colorado.
!!!Any mastiffs being adopted out of the state of Oklahoma require a health certificate to be paid for by the adopter!!!

Meet Sierra! This girl found herself in need of rescue when her owner was not able to provide for her medical care. She had scheduled a vet appointment to put Sierra down, but her family asked her to try and find someone to take Sierra instead and get her vet care completed. A good samaritan took her in to prevent her from being put down and right away reached out to Rescue for help! Sierra came to us with a very large tumor on her tail. It was bleeding and quite infected. Unfortunately the only way to remove it was to amputate her tail. She made it through surgery with flying colors and feels so much better now that is taken care of. Thankfully Sierra tested negative for heartworms! Unfortunately about a week after the first surgery, Sierra chewed her stitches out and required a 2nd surgery. About 3 days after that, the stitches failed and fell out, requiring a 3rd surgery! Poor Sierra! She did great through all of her procedures but the day after that third one, she had some kind of reaction and ended up in the ER two days in a row. Her face and legs all swelled up and she had hives on her neck and feet. We never really determined the cause of the reaction, the ER vet said she could have cancer somewhere in her body, or it was a reaction to one of the medications she is on, or a possible autoimmune disorder, or most likely a negative response to having to receive 3 surgeries in an 11 day timeframe.Sierra is on the road to recovery, her tail nub is healed up and her bloodwork is about back to normal. She lost 10 pounds during this whole ordeal and we are working on getting that back on her. Her appetite is great and she is in good spirits!Sierra is 6 years old and is AKC registered. She is showing signs of arthritis and is slow in her hind end when she gets up and down. We've started her on some medications and joint supplements to keep her comfortable. She is a very strong girl and so keeping her lean and providing light daily exercise will go far to prevent her arthritis from progressing too quickly. A home without stairs would be best for her. A couple of stairs to get in and outside is fine but going up to a 2nd story of a house is not ideal for her. Sierra is doing fine with the Mastiff in her foster home and seems to do well with medium-large size dogs. She is reported to chase anything small, so no small dogs, cats or outside pets like chickens for her. She is good with kids and loves every person she meets. She is such a sweetheart and a true velcro Mastiff - she just wants to be wherever her people are!Sierra is being fostered in Edmond, OK.Save a Mastiff...Adopt, Foster, Volunteer!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Wheeler. Big Dog Ranch Rescue saved me from a South Carolina animal shelter and I am pleased to meet you. I am very sweet and silly fellow. I have pretty low energy and I'm a guy that generally likes to keep to myself and stay out of trouble. My favorite thing in the world is getting scratched behind the ear so if you're looking to make a good first impression, that's the way to do it! I love to play with all other dogs, both big and small. Small children tend to make me nervous so an adult-only home would be preferable. I'd be a good choice for a first-time dog owner looking for a mellow dude to spend their time with. I think I'd be happiest if I could have a great big yard to run around and play in, but I would still prefer to live a quiet lifestyle with my new family. I can be a little bit protective of my territory sometimes so that's something that I would like to work on. I require some further training but I pick up on things quickly. I have been working on my leash manners and have been doing quiet well and now I love to go on long leashed walks around the ranch.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ FULL BIO
If interested in adopting, please complete form at heartsforpawsrescue.com/adopt to get started!

Meet Monty!  Monty is 9-10 month mixed mutt Rescued from Fresno SPCA as a stray so we don't know much about his life prior   

Monty is about 58 lbs and may grow to to 65-70 lbs.

Monty is already amazing in so many ways: Loving to people he knows, very well-behaved, knows basic commands (sit, down, shake), treat motivated, eager to please, no food aggression, travels well in the car, walks well on leash, loves other dogs, fine being left alone without complaint.

However, Monty needs a VERY specific and VERY special home due to stress triggers / fear-based aggression with NEW people.

Interestingly, Monty has done well meeting new people on our ranch when he is off-leash and able to “escape” as he sees it. He is either indifferent to people or will greet them quickly with loose body tail wags and then quickly move on. Out and about in the community off leash he is neutral to people and non-reactive in general (although VERY interested in squirrels and birds… the hound mix in him we think!) 

When extending a meeting w/ a new person, and/or having Monty on leash, he has growled, snarled and lunged at multiple people unprovoked if they acknowledge him. The trainers assessment is that this reactivity/wariness of people is specifically if he feels trapped or the interaction is forced. We are currently working on muzzle training, place command, look command, and sit.  If ignored, even when he’s on leash Monty is fine. 

This will require an owner who is very aware of the situations they place Monty in and ability to manage people’s interactions (please do not pet my dog); putting him away when people come over. There are so so many wonderful, easy things about Monty that we are very hopeful to find the perfect understanding, capable and skilled adopters to help him. Monty is also able to bond with/love multiple people and lives in a home with three adults + multiple dogs. The dogs help Monty very very much. He would do best in a home with 1-2+ dogs for this reason. No resource guarding of food, treats, toys against dogs in the home!

Neutered, vaccinated, vetted, microchipped and utd on preventatives 

Skin scrape negative for mange — just needs high quality diet and to stay up to date on flea tick meds

$250 adoption donation  w/ $200 training voucher available upon proof of enrollment.

Zeus - 1.5 years old, 52 lbs. Needs a home with a yard. Kids over 14.

Meet handsome Zeus! This darling boy was rescued from the streets of Mexico. He is a fairly calm boy who likes to be around his people. He is doing very well in his foster home.

Zeus is a smart boy who loves to run and play. He adores other dogs and plays well with just about any dog. He is very sweet with his people and loves affection. He can be a bit sensitive to loud or harsh voices. He needs a moment to sniff you and consider you 'good people' before he will relax around you. Zeus is potty trained and can handle being alone at home for some time if needed. He loves walks and hikes and if you are an active person he will be happy. He is no couch potato.

We prefer to see him with older kids only (over 14) as we feel that younger children may not be able to give Zeus the space he sometimes needs.

Zeus is now updated on all shots, neutered and chipped. His adoption fee is $395.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
Good day friends and welcome!

Sir Tuck at your service!

I was once a young knight hailed by the queen as the best in my class when suddenly I obtained an injury to my leg.  The royalty no longer found me useful and exiled me from my homeland.

I was discovered in park by a lovely long-haired maiden.  Ah, the way her eyes glistened in the sunlight...I digress.  She was extremely worried that I would scamper out into the lane and be trampled by one of those automatic wagons. 

She gathered me up and brought me to the magical land of Lucie.  This place is full of other knights and maidens awaiting family suitors to offer a dowry to take them to their homes.

Upon arrival, the lords and ladies took me to the "leech" or as you call it "doctor".  There it was discovered that I had a lot of muscle atrophy in my leg due to an old injury as a result of one of the many wars I fought in.

I have limited mobility in that leg now, but don't let that fool you by any means.  I am still able to run and play and defend the territory!

And do you know what else??  This cloud has a silver lining.  The lovely long-haired maiden that rescued me is now an invaluable volunteer lady here at the magical land of Lucie!

It would please me greatly if you would come to this land and meet me and the others here.  We are waiting just for YOU!!

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
PHOTOS:  Virtually all of our dogs have online PHOTO ALBUMS through SmugMug with LOTS of additional pictures.  Just copy and paste the link below into your browser (or simply type it in) and then search for the dog's "gallery" by name

          http://adoptasleddog.smugmug.com

VIDEOS:  In addition to photo albums, almost every dog has a video which will give you a much better "feel" for his or her personality.  NOTE:  In the new Petfinder format, it has become quite a bit more difficult to find and to play videos.  Please PAGE THROUGH the photos, looking for a photo overlaid in the center with a "play" arrow inside a circle.  This icon is white, so it can be difficult to see. 
 In many (most) cases, the video is the last photo displayed as you page through.  Just click on that photo and it will play.  Please make sure you CHECK ON THE PETFINDER VIDEO ICON, above, to see a video of this wonderful dog!  Our videos will include, at a minimum, whatever info we had on the dog upon (or shortly after) his/her arrival into our program.  There will sometimes be video updates as well.  And in every case, our Adoptions Coordinator can be emailed at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to answer questions and provide the most current information we have on the dog.  

NOTES:  Please see video or contact our Adoptions Coordinator at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM.

ADOPTION DONATION:  $250  Before adoption, all Northern Lights dogs (regardless of whether Petfinder's symbols appear) are spayed or neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative, fully vaccinated and tested/treated for known parasites.
 
WHAT TO DO IF YOU WANT TO ADOPT THIS DOG:  Email us at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to request an application and get started.  WE DO NOT HAVE AN ONLINE APPLICATION - you will have to request one via email.  We will review your application to determine if there is a good fit between you and/or your family and this dog.  We may suggest another dog or dog(s) if we can offer a better fit in terms of lifestyle, experience, other pets, etc.  A vet check, reference checks, and a home visit will be conducted before an adoption can be considered for approval.  
 
NORTHERN LIGHTS DOES NOT HAVE A PHYSICAL SHELTER.  We are a nonprofit rescue organization comprised of individuals who open their private homes to foster dogs in need of a second chance..  When fosters are not available, we often pay to board a dog until space is available.  New fosters and donations to pay for boarding are always desperately needed us.  Email us at KATYLIED2@AOL.COM if you are interested in donating or for information on fostering.
 
FAQ:  For information regarding our organization, as well as adoption policies and practices, please visit our Petfinder Home Page at WWW.NORTHERNLIGHTS.PETFINDER.COM.
 
 
NOTICE:  In the vast majority of cases, the dogs in our program and rescued from shelters, and Northern Lights has no means by which to collect or verify a dog's history.  We work in concert with our veterinarians, and breed and age estimates are based on a combination of professional input and our collective experience.  Our policy with information acquired prior to acceptance and while the dogs are in our care is that of "full disclosure".  It is our goal to ensure the adopter has all available information to ensure the best possible match between the dog and the adopter(s).  If we have identified a behavioral or health condition while the dog is in our care and custody, every effort will be made to correct it prior to adoption, OR the adopter will be made aware of the issue or condition prior to adoption.  Northern Lights' screening process is designed to identify only those adopters who are willing, and have the means, to treat conditions which may occur after adoption, and the adopter will be contractually responsible for doing so. However, Northern Lights' policy is to accept any adopted dog back into the program, at any time, for any reason.

animal.description:
********If dog/pup is showing as available it is available. Please do not email asking if it is. Submit application to meet dog if interested - yes an application is required********

You can learn more about our rescue and process at www.new2urescue.org or find us on facebook at https://new2urescue.org/adoption/adoption-application/ must be filled out to meet one of our dogs.  You must be 25 yrs of age or older to adopt through us. We are in the Rochester NY area and adopt dogs out to area residents.

Elmo is (we are told) a Doxie Bully mix with a touch of Schnauzer who is 2 yrs old.  We don't see the schnauzer in him but his short legs, long body and wide chest match the first two. He is only 31 lbs and looks larger than he is in photos. They also do not show how adorable he really is.
Elmo is a great boy, house trained, does well with the cat and dogs in his foster home, loves to run and play but also cuddle. He tends to bounce when running which is very entertaining to watch. He is a contradiction in one way, at his foster home he is relaxed, easy going, accepting of almost anything, can even take a bone out of his mouth. No aggression.... until a stranger comes into home. He does not like strangers and cannot be trusted with new people in home. He was surrendered as he did bite a visitor who just walked into his prior home. This is being worked on and he seems to be fine given a few minutes to accept new person but must be contained (leash/crate/etc.) when someone new comes into a home and carefully monitored while they are there.  He is amazing and almost perfect except his fear of strangers. For this reason a quieter home (not a lot of people coming and going) is the type of home he needs. Ideally you would have another dog for him to play with. He also needs a physically fenced in yard to safely run and play in.
If you are interested in meeting this adorable, goofy boy an application is required - https://www.cognitoforms.com/New2URescues/AdoptionApplication


An application must be filled out to meet any of our dogs, to apply go to 
http://new2urescue.org/adoption/adoption-application/ so foster can contact you. We do not have a shelter, dogs are in foster homes.

All animals are kept in foster homes so there is no shelter for you to visit animal. Please go to https://new2urescue.org/adoption/adoption-application/ if you would like to meet the foster animal or learn more.

All our dogs have been spayed/neutered; treated for worms; heartworm tested (if age appropriate -7 mths or older); treated for fleas/ticks; microchip; and examined by veterinarian and given age appropriate vaccinations. We take every effort to ensure the health of the animal and you will receive a copy of all vet work performed.

You can find us on Face Book at https://www.facebook.com/New2Urescue and our main website at https://www.new2urescue.org

New 2 U Rescue is registered as a New York State Shelter / Rescue. Our Registration No.: is RR033 and we are a Registered Non Profit with a 501c3. We help dogs in need in the Greater Rochester, NY area by taking them in, providing any needed vet care and helping them find a forever home.

Hi! It’s me, Gino!
Gino is a 1+-year old boy that comes from working lines, so he is a high energy Dobe. Like most of our working dogs, Gino is looking for a structured home that is going to work on his obedience training and leash skills.
Gino is a sweet boy that loves to give the “Dober-lean. Gino lived with another dog in his previous home, but the other dog was not very nice to him.
Ideally, he’s looking to be the only dog in the home.
In his previous home, Gino has struggled with meeting new people and took a while to warm up so he will require a confident handler who will recognize when he needs space and allow for slow introductions to new people. His new caretakers say that he is a social butterfly and enjoys attention from all the volunteers once he is comfortable with them so we suspect this may be something a new adopter should be aware of once he settles into a new home.
Gino is house broken, and crate trained. He is a high energy boy and will only be placed with a home with older or no children and due to his high prey drive, we’d recommend no cats or dogs, and we require a fenced in yard in a suburban or country setting. We are also requiring that the new adopter sign him up for obedience classes after the 2-week period of settling in.
Do you think Gino sounds like the right dog for you? Apply to adopt at www.dprpa.org/applicationform

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 9/21/2020
Reason for being in rescue: from feral colony
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Cody was neutered on 9/22/20. He is continuing to gain confidence and socialization and is ready for his forever home.
Weight: 45 lb
Height: 18 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Cody needs a very experienced owner that understands shy, undersocialized, or feral dogs. He is not for a first time dog owner and will not be adopted to a home without experience rescuing and helping rehabilitate dogs. Cody requires another confident dog in the home. It does not matter what size - he needs a confident canine buddy to follow, learn from, and model behaviors. Cody will not be placed in a home with children. Sudden movements and loud noises make him very nervous. He needs a quiet, consistent, patient environment.

Cody has never lived in a home. He is clean in his crate and now recognizes his crate as a safe place. Every experience will be new for this boy. If you haven't had experience helping a dog on this type of journey, Cody is not your dog.

What is my personality like? Cody has lived his entire life as part of a feral colony. He came to us as a group of dogs whose owners needed help. Their intentions were positive, but unaltered dogs breed easily and it quickly became more dogs than the family could manage, with no time to try and pet or socialize the dogs. Cody has likely never lived in a house. Everything is new!

Cody is skittish but curious about humans and how we work. So far he has learned that humans will give him a safe place to sleep where he doesn't constantly have to look over his shoulder. He's learned he won't go hungry as long as humans are near. Now it is time for Cody to learn to love. With caregivers that have been working with Cody for 6+ weeks, Cody will allow human touch. However, he does not come to you willingly and must be coaxed with treats and a gentle leash.

It should be no surprise that Cody is great with other dogs. Dogs are familiar and offer comfort. Cody needs to be with another dog and needs a dog that is confident that he can follow and learn from. He is okay with cats. He is learning to walk on a leash and doing well with it given he'd never even worn a collar 2 months ago. Cody has a gentle spirit and heart that has so much potential for love and trust. With confidence, time and patience he will make a wonderful pet.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Very shy and timid

Other tips and tidbits: Cody's estimated birthday is 9/13/2016

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

Date into Rescue: 9/28/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Lovingly surrendered by owners
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Lola is up to date on her vaccines, spayed, and looking for her forever farm!
Weight: 95 lbs
Height: 24 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Lola is looking for a farm. This beautiful girl is a working dog and wants a job. Her ideal home is on several acres of fenced land that she can roam with her family. She is good with farm animals and will protect her herd. Lola has a gentle demeanor and would do well with children.

Lola does not have good history with cats. She will kill them. For this reason she has not been tested with small dogs and will not be placed in a home with small dogs. She will not be placed in a home with cats.

Lola will not be placed as an outdoor dog. Her forever family loves and understands her breed and has the lifestyle to support her heart's desire for plenty of outside time balanced with indoor living.

What is my personality like? Lola is a big fluffy dog with a big heart of gold. She has lived her entire life on a farm. Sadly, when new owners purchased the farm, Lola began killing cats. Her heartbroken new owners reached out to Carolina Poodle Rescue for help.

Lola is cuddle bug. She adores people, adores attention, and adores being the center of attention. She is great with other big dogs. Lola is in a play group with 6 other large dogs and loves spending hours playing in the fields ever day. Lola is a working dog at heart. She takes very seriously her job of guarding and protecting farm animals and is happiest when she is outside working. She needs a job!

Since arriving in rescue Lola is learning the ropes of indoor living. She is crate trained and now happily and comfortably rests in her crate at night. She has learned sit, but will only perform basic commands if she's in the mood. She will let you leash her, but still doesn't understand why you'd need a leash to be outside walking. Lola marches to the drum of the land she is on and prefers to go with nature.

Lola is a gentle giant. Her personality has really started to shine as he has settled into rescue farm life. She is curious, playful, and a regal bundle of love.

animal.description:
Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let's get you all matched up with a loving new "furever' companion and friend. You'll find the application on the "Available Dogs" page.

NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org
Hi! I'm Capitaine Jacquouilles Noir (that's my fancy name)... but you can just call me Jack! I'm a 14 year-old cuddle bug who enjoys being with you at all times! I came into rescue because my owner passed away, but I really love my foster family and other people I meet. Since coming into DDRTX, I've been treated for mild back issues, had dental surgery, and had a benign tumour removed from my chest. I'm in pretty good shape now, but I tend to be a little itchy. I really enjoy doodling and snooping around and will get into things that I think might have food in them just like a puppy would! I love treats, sitting in laps, and yummy things I can chew on-- especially leather of all varieties! Don't think that because I'm old, I'm deaf. I can hear pretty well, I just don't really care to listen sometimes. You know what I REALLY like? My 13 year old foster brother. I follow him EVERYWHERE. I walk on the leash with him, go in the car with him, am nice to cats with him, and give him kisses because I just adore him. I just think he's amazing and my foster family is surprised at how quickly and strongly I bonded to him! I am pretty well house broken and can use a doggie door, but you have to remember to take me out to potty! I also like to talk to you when I want something... it can a treat, a pet, a hug, a game of tug with a toy.... I do it every night to my human foster brother- BARK BARK BARK! I'm looking for a family who understands that any leather within my reach is game, that I'm way more crafty and spry than you're going to give me credit for (I will find a way on your work desk), and who wants a wonderful cuddle buddy for tv and bedtime.
Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. animal.description: If you are looking for an agility dog, look no further than Michigan! This girl has hops! Around 2 years old, Michigan is likely a mix of many breeds but we think she's got some Miniature Pinscher and Terrier in her. She diligently cared for her pups but now she's ready to put parenthood behind her for a home to call her very own. Michigan is the absolute sweetest girl who made herself right at home in her foster home (and on the couch!). She knows sit and is very treat motivated. Michigan is also house trained in her current foster home. She can jump very high and easily scale at least a 5 foot fence so shouldn't be left home alone in the yard. She has A LOT of energy in a small package and will need an active home with a yard and either an equally playful dog friend and/or someone looking for a new running buddy. Once she gets her zoomies out, she is quite content to sleep and cuddle for a few hours. Michigan loves to play with kids but can get a little mouthy when excited. She gets along with other dogs and enjoys playing with them at the park. She is a total cuddlebug and eager to please. If you are interested in meeting Michigan or any of our dogs or puppies, please submit an adoption application on our website. If you have adopted from us before or are already approved with an adoption coach, please reach out to your coach for the next steps. This information is as up to date and accurate as possible for the dog in its current environment. All dogs and puppies will need time and training to adjust to their new surroundings and to learn the rules of their new home. If you are interested in meeting one of our dogs, the first step is to complete the Adoption Form on our website at www.labsandmore.org and take some time to review our adoption process. Your adoption includes the spay or neuter, current vaccinations, microchip, and other services provided while in our care. The safety and health of our puppies is priority one, so we only allow approved applicants to meet and handle puppies. Please understand everything we do is for the dogs and conducted by our kind and generous volunteers. We rely solely on donations, and we do not profit from a dog's adoption. Labs and More is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization that operates on donations and time dedicated to this cause by volunteers. Your adoption will save the life of future dogs in need. Labs and More makes no guarantees regarding the behavior, breed, or age of the dogs in our care. Although we strive to provide necessary medical care to dogs in our care, we cannot predict future or current medical needs whether they were symptomatic or not at the time of adoption.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
Jane is an incredibly sweet, silly, derpy Bull Breed mix who is looking for the right home. She promises to entertain you with her endless hilarious antics, snuggle and watch movies and probably douse you in kisses. She is an absolute ham, that anyone would be lucky to have as a companion.
She is wonderful with people, but can be dog selective as we've realized with more dog greets. She does not like all dogs she meets, and therefore we are asking that she go home as an only dog or with only one male dog who she meets beforehand. She is a no for cats, no exceptions will be made.
Jane is a very hyper and high drive dog, who has a lot of love and life to give. She knows basic obedience, is crate trained and crates on command, is potty trained and is the biggest love you'll ever meet. We are asking for no small children, as she has no idea of her size and hyper ness and would knock a child over but she loves older children and thinks they are meant just for her.
Jane comes with free training and we would like a family who will attend these, as it's important she stays mindful. With her hyper nature and pickiness towards other dogs, this is very important. Jane will be spayed, vaccinated and chipped before leaving. Please message the page or text 775-303-8364 to meet Jane.Our dogs are spayed/neutered and utd on shots before adoption unless medically not advised by our Vet.

animal.description:
My name is LOBO and I'm approximately 8 years and 2 months old male germ shepherd. I have been at the Agoura Animal Care Center since October 22, 2020. 

Lobo so deserves a new beginning!?
•
8 year old Lobo arrived from our Downey Animal Care Center back in October. We suspect he didn’t receive the best care with his prior family??

When he came to the care center, he had severely  infected ears so we have been treating them and he's feeling so much better now.  Despite his rough living in the past, he remains a very happy boy!   

He adores humans, walks well on leash, enjoys a stuffie, likes to play fetch, is very affectionate.

He is a glutton for attention and appreciates being brushed, & loves a stuffed kong. At first, he was very unsure about going into our real room...we’re guessing his past 8 years have been spent mainly living outside, but he's definitely getting better! 
•
We’d love to find Lobo an indoor home  where he can become a beloved family member. Best placement would be a home with older children (MS age & up), a calm large dog companion could also be a consideration. 
•
To meet our sweet senior Lobo please email agoura@animalcare.lacounty.gov (Please include your contact number).

Hansel is working on house training and some basic manners. If you would like to make Hansel a part of your family, fill out an application at www.barktownrescue.org.
HANSEL'S ADOPTION FEE IS $170The shelter software system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at the dog's predominant breed or breed mix. We strongly encourage you to select your new pet by looking at each dog's individual personality and pet qualities rather than relying on a breed label that is only our best guess.

Our adoption fees vary from $150 and up. All of our dogs are up to date on vaccines, heart worm preventives, and flea/tick medication, and will be spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Portions of your adoption fee also help care for the sick and injured animals that we take in. Thank you for supporting us and considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Lady is a 4-6 year old boxer mix.

Her adoption fee is $150. She is spayed, current on vaccines and microchipped.

Lady's adoption application can be found at this link: https://petstablished.com/public/search/pet/156759

a note from her foster mom... 

As I sit and watch Lady play in the backyard with her current playmate, one of many of her playmates that have come and gone while she remains in foster care, I wonder why no one is willing to take a chance on her. Shes such a happy, bouncy loving girl. Its been 2 years since Lady came to us from the local over-crowded kill shelter. Still, she waits for a family of her own.

Lady isnt unique in appearance, she doesnt stand out in a crowd, shes not a puppy, shes not a tiny lap dog, she isnt even fluffy. She does take a couple of treats (shes highly bribable!) to get comfortable with people she doesnt know, mainly men. She doesnt care much for strangers crowding her when shes in her crate, but who would? Lady is incredibly loving and loyal. She loves with her whole heart. Shes got to be one of the most deserving dogs that has come through our doors. Still, she waits.

Lady sits, she lays down, she rolls over, shes crate trained and 100% house trained. Still, she waits.

Lady has a beautiful playful nature, she loves to play chase with her playmates. If she is alone she doesnt mind grabbing a toy and playing by herself. Sitting and watching her as she tosses a toy for herself and happily retrieves it to toss around some more is one of the most adorable things Ive ever seen. She absolutely loves stuffed toys. She gently carries them around, cares for them and takes them to bed with her. Its absolutely adorable. Still, she waits.

While our beautiful bouncy girl has a couple of easily workable quirks, she has still been looked over time and time again. She watches as so many other dogs come and go. On to their forever families filled with love. Lady wants nothing more than the same for herself. We want nothing more than the same for her. Still, she waits.
animal.name: Lady

Yabba-dabba-do, this duo is for you!! Meet Betty & Barney, a precious mother & son bonded pair of one and two-year-old, 55 lb. pitties. Found as strays, they sadly ended in a kill shelter. With only hours remaining, Happily Furever After Rescue scooped them up just in time!! These cuties are ready to start their next adventure up north in Connecticut. 

Betty (F) and Barney (M) are an inseparable pair who LOVE to snuggle and play! You can find them chasing after one another in the yard, lounging in the sun, or giving each other kisses. They're such good pups and are house and crate-trained. They presently live in a home with other dogs and are fine with them. We do not recommend a home with cats or young children. Kids 8+ potentially ok. You MUST have a fenced yard to be considered for their adoption.

Currently they're available to foster, adopt, or you can choose to foster-to-adopt. They are extremely bonded so they MUST go to a home together, no exceptions. Betty & Barney's adoption fee is $400 total and they are up to date on vaccines, microchipped, heartworm negative, and altered. Six months ago Betty had undergone heartworm treatment and is now also negative. If you are interested in adopting this sweet pair, please complete the application at form.jotform.com/200883908893166 or email info@happilyfureverafter.org.

If interested, please

complete the

Adoption Application

on our website at

www.NeedyPaws.org

and we will contact you.

Adopters must live within an hour's drive of St. Louis, MO.

Our $250 adoption fee includes up-to-date vaccinations, heartworm testing and preventative, spay/neuter and microchip.

LEGO is an 11 month old, male, Louisiana Catahoula mix. He was found in a rural area as a stray. This young boy is the whole package! He is house trained, knows some basic manners, crate trained, and is friendly with other dogs and cats. LEGO likes kids, but it is important to keep in mind with kids that LEGO is a herding dog. His breed by nature is to herd. He is mouthy and can try to nip heels to "keep you in line". These behaviors can be overwhelming for small children. LEGO needs a home with a FENCED YARD to give him a place to exert some of his energy and an active family! He is not just some couch potato! LEGO would love another playful dog to be in his home!

Breed experience is highly recommended due to LEGO's classic Catahoula traits! This breed is familiar with hard work and long days! Their stamina is high and needs a "job" to keep them busy and their mind from wondering to destructive behaviors. This breed needs a firm owner to keep them on task and provide a challenging environment full of enrichment activities, both physically and mentally.

We are a 100% foster-based rescue and all of our dogs live in approved foster homes. We are dedicated to finding the best Forever Homes, and will perform home visits and conduct veterinarian and reference checks for each potential adopter.

animal.description:
Meet Jazzy!! Jazzy's shelter name was Jazz, and the handlers liked the name, so they decided to keep it, but make it just a little well jazzier!! So Jazzy it is! Jazzy had been a shelter dog more than once - that's just so sad. She was owned by someone who developed health problems and couldn't care for her, so she was relinquished to the shelter. She was adopted again, and
...

not long after that, came back in much worse condition than she left. She was tethered in the second owner's front yard, she had significant hair loss, and was underweight - the note was made that it appeared as though she had not eaten in several days. She was treated for her skin condition, and she gained some weight. She developed an upper respiratory infection and was treated, and she gained some weight. She was spayed and recovered, and gained some weight. All in all, this not-so-little girl gained 23 pounds at the shelter, and is more than slightly rubenesque!! We think she was eating her food, and as much of everyone else's food as she could - poor thing probably just couldn't get past feeling so very hungry!

We were drawn to her sunny disposition, so we temperament tested her, and we were thrilled when she passed!! After 185 days in the shelter, she was finally going to get to leave!! This chubby girl (we will work on her weight!!) is a sharpei / pit mix, with a golden brown coat, and smiling face. She does love so very much to give kisses - and we have the pictures to prove it!! She is extremely playful, and loves to engage in toy games with her people.

Want to help us make sure that the rest of Jazzy's days are full of fun, without any chains or missed meals? Put your application in today - www.caninecellmates.org!

Jazzy is located in Atlanta, GA and is available for adoption immediately. Jazzy is spayed, microchipped and up to date on all her shots. Canine CellMates dogs are trained in items similar to the Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. They learn basic obedience and commands such as sit, down, stay, go to place, and leave it. They are also crate trained. If you are interested in adopting Jazzy, please fill out an adoption application at www.caninecellmates.org. or email adopt@caninecellmates.org for more information.

animal.description:
Introducing OLIVER, a very easy going, relaxed, "gentleman" seeking his forever family and home. Oliver is around 10 years old and currently weighs 25 pounds; we think he is a Jack Russell Terrier mix. Oliver is a very sweet boy who deserves a quiet home with an adopter who has a lot of love to give.

Oliver really enjoys having his head, snout, and belly rubbed. He loves to sleep and snuggle in a blanket on the bed or couch. Oliver is not really interested in playing with other dogs, but he's perfectly fine living with them. He'll play with a toy or bone for a short period of time, but loses interest after a little while; Oliver's more into people than other dogs or toys. But, he does enjoy going for walks. He does love treats and eats well.

Because Oliver is older and he has a little arthritis in his back end, he is not appropriate for young children who would try to lay on or be rough with him. This sweet dog gets a bit anxious when his foster mom leaves the house - but it's totally understandable - so he needs an adopter who is home most of the day. Prior to his rescue, Oliver was abandoned on a back porch of his home for a month when his family moved out and away. Despite this horrible trauma, Oliver is doing very well in foster care.

ADOPTION APPLICATIONS are available by request at acaringplace@comcast.net The adoption fee for Oliver is $250. Oliver is in good health and is fully vetted, had a senior blood panel run (no concerns) and has been neutered and microchipped; he does have a condition where one of his is small and shrinking but it is not painful nor life threatening. A Caring Place - All Breed Dog Rescue adopts throughout the Greater Chicagoland Area. All dogs and puppies live in foster homes, providing you as the adopter, with information on the animal's behaviors, needs, and requirements. We are always in search of fosters care providers. If you are one of those special people willing to open your heart and home to an animal in need and would like to receive information on how you can foster an animal, please contact us.

animal.description:
Joey is one of nine Chihuahuas who lived with a Senior Couple and the couple became concerned they were becoming unable to take care of them properly.  When the couple asked for help finding homes for the Chihuahuas, of course, Chloe's Pet Rescue stepped up and brought them into the rescue.  The Chi's were loved and taken care of to the best of their ability.   

Joey, along with most of them are skittish around new people.  We are sure he will blossom and get over being skittish with patience and time, along with being loved by his new "furever" family.

If you are interested in adding Joey to your family, please go to our website and complete an application for adoption.   The adoption fee is $225, which includes his full vetting (three adult dog vaccinations, microchip, de-worming, heartworm preventative, and neuter).

animal.description: If you are applying for Delilah, please indicate on your application that you have read and understand her specific needs. Delilah is simply delightful! She is a 14 week old, 14 lb. Blue French Bulldog mix. She is a happy, playful puppy with 'big dog' energy, often playing tumble with her Lab/Great Dane canine friend. Despite the challenges she is working to overcome, she is unstoppable and has such a zest for life! Delilah was born with Spina Bifida and does not have full use of her back legs and is not fully continent. Don't be fooled though, this girl can really move! She plays a mean game of tug of war, and her 'fetch' game is beyond adorable. After her morning meal and play session, Delicious Delilah loves to spend her day relaxing and snoozing on the lap of her foster mom while she works. She is the star of the Zoom meetings! It does take some time and patience to care for Delilah, but it's so worth it! You will be rewarded with tons of licks and kisses. And did I mention that she is the best snuggler? She is a love-bug! Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY. You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/). All fields on the application must be completed. Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit. Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application. We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application. If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you. We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) Thanks so much.

animal.description:
Hello ""handsome blockhead Ralphie!!!

This guy is awesome - super playful with other dogs in daycare.. attends daycare at John Gagnon's Pet Resort and has a blast! He has challenges with other dogs on leash and so city living is not for this boy. Fenced yard where he can run and entertain himself is key. 

Ralphie is used to living with women only and he's proving to us that is all he will tolerate at this point. Someone with breed experience who is open to training could make this happen but a a woman or same sex woman couple would be ideal for this boy. We don't believe children are in his future.

So yes, he has many challenges but we are willing to help as much as possible with behavior support. 

Back Story 
Ralphie's mom sadly is not doing well health-wise and is moving in with family - she also has a 14 yo female bulldog that she will be taking with her but she feels in her heart that Ralphie needs a more full life going forward- someone who will take him place, hiking, exercise him more than she can now. She is doing this after a lot of thought and recommendation by her dog trainer as Ralphie is very attached to she and the other dog - he is super protective of them and is a different dog when they around. By moving him she knows he will go on to be not protective and enjoy life as a regular dog, not super protector.

Ralphie is currently residing at John Gagnon's where he's doing great. We have volunteers signing up to take him for walks and he does really well when out and about. His mom tells us he's 100% housetrained but he won't bark or give overt signs he needs to go out - you need to learn his signals!!

John Gagnon will be personally involved in this adoption to answer any questions you have about this boy - he calls him a rock star and wants to be sure he gets in the very best home possible.

Name: Ralphie
Breed: English Bulldog/Crossbreed
Sex: Male
Age: 7 years 0 months
Weight: 60
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Negative
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS: 
Good with Children: Unknown
Good with Dogs: Absolutely
Good with Cats: Unknown

Adoption Fee: $300.00


IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.

At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.


NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

Sweet Gus arrived at our shelter after being struck by a vehicle. His front leg and his hip were injured. He had FHO surgery and his leg is mending.  All that's left for Gus to do is heal and gain strength in the coming weeks. Gus is between 1 and 2 years old and his weight is about 70 lb. He is a striking boy. He has a sparkling personality and loves company.  He is good with other dogs but not cats. Gus knows a few commands and is eager to please. He enjoys playing with his toys and would love to have a canine sibling to call his own. Although we feel Gus would enjoy smaller children, he is young , extremely playful, not to mention a big dog and most likely would play to rough for a small child or elderly person. It should also be known that he has a typical Shepherd personality and will be on guard with strangers. A slow meet and greet is recommended for new folks. Once he accepts you he will be loyal, playful and happily social. 
He is living in foster care with other dogs. He is housebroken and fairly well mannered in the house. His activity should be fairly low for the next few weeks until his hip is fully recovered.
