animal.description:
STORMIE!!!
GOOD with dogs, GOOD with kids 8+, NO cats

ADOPTION FEE $400    www.unbreakabull.com/adopt

What’s in a name you ask? Well, for me, Stormie fits me perfectly as that has been what my life has been like up until coming into rescue. My beginning story is not very well known, but I was found last winter during a sub-zero, stormy, winter night tied to a pole outside the shelter. I spent the next 10 months living in the shelter scared and so shy of people and my environment. No one ever came to claim me, but the hopes were small due to being tied up outside. I was passed over by a lot of rescues because of being so scared, but Unbreakabull saw me and took a chance, and I have not disappointed. Despite my name, I am the sweetest girl that you will ever meet!! I am 3 years old, and I absolutely love other dogs. I love to play with toys as well. I am doing great on my leash when I go for walks, but I will try and chase anything that is small like squirrels and birds that I can see, so we think that it’s best that I not be around cats. I currently live with 2 other dogs, and I absolutely love them! I do great when playing with them, and I even enjoy some random snuggle time. I am still a little hesitant when it comes to new people and will act shyly and be very nervous around them. I am protective of new people coming into my space, but once I get comfortable around people, like my foster family, I settle in a little more. I am going to need someone who can take things slowly with me. I got to experience a new snow fall, and I loved running around in it and trying to eat it! Apparently being left out in the cold didn’t affect my desire to enjoy the white stuff that came from the sky. Due to be still so nervous around people and sounds and quick movements, it’s best that I be with children that are a little older and can understand that I just need time to warm up to them and that I don’t like sudden things happening. I don’t bite or growl, I just get anxious and scared. I know how to sit, shake with BOTH paws, and I am learning to stay and wait for whatever I am being asked to wait for. Usually it’s a treat, so I don’t mind :) . While my life may have started out as a storm, all that I currently see is the rainbow that comes after the storm in the quiet. If you think that you could be my lifetime rainbow partner, please head on over and fill out an application so that we can meet. Until I get to see you, I’ll keep working on getting some more treats and building my confidence. Always rainbows, Stormie (UPDATED 12/23/20)


Too see more pictures and videos of me visit my page at 
https://www.unbreakabull.com/stormie

animal.description:
Welcome to Grace Rescue, HAYLEY, twenty-five pounds of the sweetest, young, purebred Beagle girl you could ever hope to find! 

Hayley was rescued from the Olive Branch Animal Shelter and was taken straight to our vet in Olive Branch where she was estimated to be about 3 years old—a truly great age for a Beagle. She is young but is more settled, no hyper puppy energy. Everyone from Nikki, the Animal Control Officer at the shelter, to Dr. Ginny, Haley’s doctor, and everyone in between have declared her the absolute sweetest tempered little dog. She was very cooperative at the clinic. Her bloodwork was “perfect,” Dr. Ginny’s word, except for being,  understandably, slightly anemic. Fortunately, she has no intestinal parasites. She has infected skin around her neck,  but absolutely nothing we cannot fix. She will look like Miss Doggie America when Dr. Ginny works her magic. 

Hayley is walking well on leash, thanks to training she is receiving from Michelle at our vet clinic. She is still a bit timid, but that too will improve with time as she trusts us more and more. 

Hayley is being fostered through heartworm treatment by a family who has been approved also to adopt Hayley. The reason she is listed as “adoption pending” is because we never finalize an adoption of any of our dogs while they are undergoing heartworm treatment. Her foster family loves her and has every intention of adopting her as soon as she completes treatment. We encourage you, however, to visit our full Petfinder site and see ALL the precious Beagles we have available. We welcome your applying to foster-to-adopt one of our available Beagles, already in various stages of vetting. Please visit also our rescue Facebook page where we post updates, pictures, and videos of all of our dogs. Petfinder limits us on the number of pictures and videos we can post. Facebook does not.

animal.description: Oh my heart!!  We love this gal! She is sooooo sweet, so mellow—& truly a Diamond in the Ruff.  She gives the most sincere eye contact you can imagine, and it is clear she is sending you her love. Diamond is a straight-up people person.  She had a rough start in our Pups on Parole program. The minute she arrived, we had to send her out for exploratory surgery, not knowing if she would live or die. Luckily, her issue was completely resolved. She is healing and on a low activity regimen, so there are things we haven’t been able to learn about her yet. She was surrendered to the local shelter for being an “escape artist.” We suspect, from observing her gentle temperament, that in actuality she was not getting enough human attention. Her handler reports her as being a medium energy dog who is great on a leash, mainly because his (YOUR) company nearby is what Diamond most wants.  She  is house-broken. Diamond has spent telling lengths of time unattended in areas where she easily could have done damage, but instead she waited contentedly for her handler to return.  She is not a destructive chewer. She listens to and accepts verbal corrections. At this point, being unable to test Diamond out with our resident cat, we are going to recommend against adopting her to a home with cats. We think she would be great with kids. She weighs about 50 pounds. This girl needs a home where they need her as much as she needs them. If you think Diamond could be your FOREVER dog please use the information below to inquire. To get more information on a Pups On Parole dog, please contact a representative of the Lassen Humane Society at 530 251-7247 or e-mail ilovepopdogs@yahoo.com.  The Pups On Parole Program started in June of 2007 to help give homeless dogs a second chance at finding an adoptive family.  All dogs in the program spent time in our local county shelter, surrendered by their owners or picked up as strays and waiting for their owners to redeem them or to be adopted by new families.   The selected dogs are brought current on vaccinations, spayed/neutered if necessary, micro chipped, and heart worm tested.  They then are taken to the California Correctional Center Firehouse where they are assigned to a trainer/ inmate fire fighter.  These trainers groom and work with each dog and give them the extra time and attention they need to become wonderful family companions.   Most graduates are house trained and know basic obedience commands.  As of December 2018, 535 dogs have been adopted through this program.  To meet any of the Pups On Parole dogs, arrangements must be made in advance.

animal.description:
Lulu Belle is a tricolor female Beagle mix that grew up in a tough part of town.  Besides the elderly man that took this girl under his wing, the other neighborhood residents were not very kind to her.  Lacking resources to properly care for Lulu Belle and fearing for her safety, he reached out to us for help.  Fortunately, we were able to bring her into our rescue recently and she is doing quite well.  At first, Lulu Belle was understandably wary of volunteers.  It has been a journey gaining her trust.  With patience and love, our volunteers showed her not all people were bad and soon won her over.  This girl has really blossomed over the past few weeks and is now ready to be adopted.  Lulu Belle is approximately one and half years old, medium in size, and has been fully vetted.  She would make a wonderful companion for someone that is home most of the day.  Lulu Belle would do best if she had another confident dog to bond with.  She tends to be anxious and fearful of children because of prior abuse suffered at their hands.  Older children that are dog savvy and respectful would likely gain her trust.  She is fond of some of our teenage volunteers.  LuLu Belle will need a fenced in yard at her new home.  She is not accustomed to leashed walks but does enjoy playing and running outdoors. Lulu Belle prefers going on grass and is housebroken if kept on a regular schedule.  This girl is a very affectionate loving dog that deserves a second chance. Please consider opening your heart and give Lulu Belle the loving home she so desperately needs.  

To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

animal.description:
Experienced dog home wanted!! Chance is a 2 year old mix breed that traveled all the way from Arkansas in search of his happy ending. He was adopted recently, but had to come back for some behavioral issues that arose in the home. Chance will need an experienced dog owner to help him reach his full potential! He is a very smart man, but it does not seem as though he was taught many skills from a young age. His recent training with a Gentle Leader has proven to help immensely with his overall behavior while interacting with humans. He is making wonderful strides in basic obedience, with SIT and DOWN being his current triumphs! Chance is very food motivated, so training is proving to be easy and FUN! Chance's new home will need to continue using this gentle leader and should also seek training classes, which will help strengthen the bond between him and his new home! Chance would be best in a home as an only pet and with children 15+. His ideal family would be home often, as he does not like being left alone. If you think that you can give Chance the home that he deserves, please visit our webpage www.spfldhumane.org to fill out an application for adoption!
Adoption Fee: $200 (includes Gentle Leader)

NOTE: WE ARE CURRENTLY ONLY ADOPTING TO VERMONT RESIDENTS.

1. Everyone must submit an application before an appointment is set to meet the dogs. We work BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

2. Meet with the dog(s)

3. Verification of Home

4. Adoption Contract

5. Bring treats

The adoption fee helps cover expenses for all dogs while in the rescue program including the vet exams, vaccines, heartworm testing and treatment, stool check, spay/neuter, monthly Heartworm & Flea preventative plus other necessary veterinary care and training to get the dog ready for adoption.

Your support, both through adoption and donation is always essential to us and our rescue dogs. Donate today.

animal.description:
Meet Akira. Akira is a silly, loving girl overall. She is slowly starting to warm up to her foster. She hates the snow to say the least. She's a counter surfer. Also she eats in very quickly so the foster has changed her to a slow feeder. Foster is looking forward to working with this little girl, teaching her some manners and seeing her grow

SPECIAL NEEDS

She was surrendered to Veterinary Emergency and Specialty Hospital for medical issues suffering from multiple seizures and extremely thin from consistent throwing up and diarrhea. Akira's labs did not show a reason for her generalized seizure disorder. She has a diagnosis of juvenile epilepsy. Statistically, most likely ideopathic epilepsy that after achieving control on anti epileptic drugs for at least 6 months may begin to very gradually wean off medications( like 4 to 12month weaning period). After her seizure early morning October 21st and starting phenobarbital, she has not had further seizure activity. She will need blood levels checked for phenobarb once or twice and regular checks of those and liver values every 6months while on the meds.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Beau Geste was purchased as a puppy from a breeder in South Carolina, but was surrendered to a local rescue several years later because he was fearful and had a bite history. He was adopted out as an emotional support dog and, although loved, wasn't cut out for the job and his behavior only escalated. Beau can only be placed with a very experienced handler who has no children living in or regularly visiting the home, and they must be very adept at reading dog body language. Beau gets along well with other dogs and dog-savvy cats but has human aggression, and will need to wear a muzzle when near unfamiliar people or teaching new commands. He has been with his foster for more than two months and, while he has shown improvement in many areas, including better restraint in misplaced aggression and cession of human resource guarding, he is still displaying "nip and run" behavior. Because of the misplaced aggression, an e-collar cannot be used and any correction (verbal or physical) that Beau perceives as too harsh elicits an aggressive response. Beau has received extensive obedience training, and his foster is currently working on behavior modification, which takes much longer to fix. Beau will need a very special adopter who is 100% committed to him.If you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

She does okay with other male dogs when properly introduced, but can be selective and it's mainly with female dogs. She's non reactive to cats, but hasn't been up close yet and interacted with one yet. Micah is now officially 100% crate trained and 100% potty trained. We'd recommend no children 10 & under. Although she is great with all people and craves human companionship along with tons of attention, Micah does like her own personal space. She knows all of her basic commands and is just a lover at the end of the day.

Adoption #Requirements: No Exceptions
- Fenced in Yard Required
- No kids under the age of 10
- No Female Dogs

Micah is currently up for adoption through Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue. Her adoption fee is $350 & will include her distemper, rabies, bordetella, parvo, & lepto vaccines; deworming; microchip; heartworm test; fecal test & being fixed. Micah is currently on both flea & tick, as well as heartworm prevention. We kindly ask that you please wait until then to ask any questions.

***PLEASE READ THIS ENTIRE POST & FOLLOW THE INSTRUCTIONS****
 
With the Covid-19 Pandemic going on we are still doing adoptions, but please remember that we are all volunteers and safety comes first. With our rescue being based in the Metro Detroit area, all prospective adopters must live within the state of Michigan (which means No out of state adoptions). Please remember we are not a shelter and are 100% foster based. Once you submit your application, it may take up to 2 weeks for us to get back to you. So please be patient with us.

Again, we kindly ask that you please read the entire post to answer your questions. If you cannot follow the instructions properly, we will skip your application and move onto the next one. We kindly ask that you save any questions, comments or concerns for the phone interview. We kindly ask the following: No phone calls, No pm's, & No multiple emails- We are all volunteers and promise to get back to you within a timely fashion! 
 
Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue; previously known as the PRO-PET-OTIC Foundation, is a 100% Foster-Based Rescue that is ran by all Volunteers. Which means that we are not a shelter & each animal is in an actual home with a foster family. We kindly ask that you put any questions within the email & our team of Volunteers will get back to you. With the overwhelming amount of emails please be patient with our 100% volunteer family and we will get back to you. The application MUST BE filled out, a Vet Check MUST BE completed by our team, as well as a phone interview before we do a 'Meet N Greet.'
 
Vet Checks:
When adopting through our rescue, we 'ALWAYS' do a vet check on each applicant's pets that they have owned over the past 10 years. Please make sure to call your vet to grant them permission to release this information to our rescue. That being said, all of the animals in each applicant's home must be UTD on all of their vaccines (DHLPP & Rabies), an UTD Heartworm Test, & currently on both Flea & Tick, as well as Heartworm Prevention. So please make sure that when you are applying that all of your current animals go to the vet that is listed.
 
How To Apply:
If you're interested in adopting one of our available dogs:
1. Email LendingaHelpingPaw313@gmail.com with the dogs name as the subject when you ask for the adoption application.
2. Once you have completed the application, please print it out, fill it out, scan it, & then email it back to LendingAHelpingPaw313@gmail.com. If you do not have a scanner, please take a picture with your phone and we kindly ask that you sent all attachments into one email.
3. Please make sure to call your vet to grant our organization permission to do a vet check on your current pet.
4. If you are interested in more than one dog, please list your top 3 choices on the completed application.
5. Please be honest & truthful on your application. We always do a vet Check. We always do a home visit. And we always have both the prospective families & dogs best interest at heart!

Thank you in advance for all of your love & support,
The Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue Family

animal.description: Belgium is currently recovering from knee surgery and will be available for adoption in late January or early February. Belgium is just about as sweet as can be! She is a little Terrier mix close to 25 lbs. She came to Labs and More with her 8 puppies. After being the best little mama to her pups, she is finished with motherhood and nearly ready for a home of her own. Now that she's done with her puppies, this little mama is letting her inner puppy out! Belgium is very sweet and gets along with everyone she meets - people, dogs and cats. She does seem to do better with small to medium dogs and avoids larger dogs when she can. Like many Terriers, she does nip at your heels and during playtime, something she is working on correcting in her foster home, but she may not be the best choice for families with small children at this time. She loves kids and does well with older children. She revels in attention and sitting with you on your lap. She will need a family that lets her up on the furniture because she enjoys cuddling on the couch with you. She sleeps on the couch in her foster home through the night but would love to sleep in bed with you instead. One bonus about this girl is she doesn't shed! She is house trained in her current foster home. Belgium is food motivated and is sneaky enough to try to swipe food off countertops. She comes when called, knows what "no" means, and has good leash manners. She loves her walks and has medium energy with the occasional burst of high energy zoomies. She would benefit from a home with a yard where she can play fetch, run around to her heart's content, and maybe dig a few holes. She wouldn't mind being your next running buddy for short jogs. This little girl wants to be wherever her people are. She would prefer a home where her humans are home more often than not and work from home. Belgium is an easygoing, always tail wagging, happy little pup that will make a great family dog. If you are interested in meeting Belgium or any of our dogs or puppies, please submit an adoption application on our website. If you have adopted from us before or are already approved with an adoption coach, please reach out to your coach for the next steps. This information is as up to date and accurate as possible for the dog in its current environment. All dogs and puppies will need time and training to adjust to their new surroundings and to learn the rules of their new home. If you are interested in meeting one of our dogs, the first step is to complete the Adoption Form on our website at www.labsandmore.org and take some time to review our adoption process. Your adoption includes the spay or neuter, current vaccinations, microchip, and other services provided while in our care. The safety and health of our puppies is priority one, so we only allow approved applicants to meet and handle puppies. Please understand everything we do is for the dogs and conducted by our kind and generous volunteers. We rely solely on donations, and we do not profit from a dog's adoption. Labs and More is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization that operates on donations and time dedicated to this cause by volunteers. Your adoption will save the life of future dogs in need. Labs and More makes no guarantees regarding the behavior, breed, or age of the dogs in our care. Although we strive to provide necessary medical care to dogs in our care, we cannot predict future or current medical needs whether they were symptomatic or not at the time of adoption.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description: This is Mary! She's around two years old with lots of life to live and love to give. This pitbull sweetie is currently getting lots of love in a great foster home while she waits for her forever family to find her. Mary is housetrained, walks well on a leash and knows a handful of commands! She isn't super friendly with other pups or kids, but she's working on it! She's a very affectionate girl who loves cuddling with her people on the couch. As for toys, she really enjoys a good rope or squeaky toy. This girl is the total package - loves to play but loves to be calm with her people, too. As for a home, she would love a family with patience as she gets to know them. She has so much love to give and will be the perfect companion. She would love a backyard to play in and a family who will let her fully participate in their lives - going for walks, on car rides, letting her sit with them on the couch. She just wants a family of her own. Could that family be yours? Apply to adopt Mary today! All Dallas Pets Alive adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon adoption. The standard minimum donation for dogs over six months to seven years is $200, puppies under six months is $250, dogs eight years and over are $100 unless specified otherwise. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallaspetsalive.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/ . For more information, you can email adopt@dallaspetsalive.org.

animal.description:
Please read the dog's entire bio before you apply.  Sadly, we are no longer able to respond to every application, but will contact the one that is a good match within 3 days.
Chief is a male terrier mix, a little 11.5 lb boy who has a ton of wiry black/silver hair and very expressive eyes.   Chief is 3-4 yrs old.   He is shy at first but does want to trust, he just takes a little time.  Chief is not great on the leash yet (too scared) and would need a quiet place to come out of his shell.   He does well with other small dogs and is very respectful with them.  He bonds to one person is the home so a quieter home with just one caretaker is likely best for him.
Most of our dogs are not available to an out of the area adoption because of difficulty to follow up.  If you do not live within a 2 hr drive of Orange County, please email us before applying to see if the dog you are interested is may be a candidate for long distance adoption.    We only make consider long distance adoptions for dogs who have been in our rescue for 6 plus months with no local candidates.
If you are interested in adopting one of our rescues, please visit our main website for adoption procedures at www.pupsandpals.net and then fill out our application.  Please note that we are all volunteers so it may take up to 3 days to process your application, but you will hear back from us if your application is a good match for the pet. 
We do not have a shelter so individual appointments must be made to meet the pet you are interested in.  Our pets are fostered/boarded all over LA and Orange County.  
This pet is altered, vaccinated, microchipped, and has had a brief temperament evaluation to help us determine what type of  a home he/she would thrive in.  Please note that we put lots of time and effort to make sure our pets are ready to be someone's perfect pet before they go home.... and to make sure that we will have the best possible match for this pet we do require an : application, interview, adoption fee and in some case a home check.  
Listed for adoption: 11/2/2020
Adoption fee: $350
PLEASE DO NOT call or email to see if a pet is available.  We update our pages daily so if he/she is pictured here in the available dogs section, we are accepting applications at this time.

animal.description:
Angus came to us when we were contacted by the local dog pound about a black lab a citizen had carried in because he was unable to stand.   We first suspected a spinal injury but xrays showed a broken pelvis and hip.  Xrays also showed that his growth plates aren't fused which puts him at big puppy age. 

This sweet guy has healed up well and in just three weeks after we got him, he's up to about 75% of normal activity with only a slight limp which we think will completely vanish when a little more time has passed. 

He took great to crate training.  He wants to please. He fetches some but doesn't seem to have a super high ball drive.  He is not sufficiently house trained to be left alone in the house but he's never had an accident in the house either.   He will try to sneak your shoes into his crate.  He loves toys and always has his tail in a slow wag.

He gets along great with a senior German Shepherd in his foster home.  He annoys the heck out of our very bold, non fearful cat but hasn't shown any aggression.  He would probably chase after a cat that would run but he's not shown any prey drive.   He has growled at the other dog when he's eating but we've scolded and redirected his behavior and he's responsive. 

He is not likely a purebred Labrador Retriever but he's very "labby" in both appearance and disposition.  He's about 60 pounds and really handsome. 

An adoption application and $149 adoption fee is required.

animal.description:
Meet Lily! This silly, sweet 6 year old pup and her best friend Jessi are looking for a special home. Both girls have some ongoing medical needs that ARF is taking care of, but they would love a home that offers love, comfy beds, and a great retirement plan. Though Lily is younger, she is definitely the big sister of the two, always looking out for Jessi. Both Lily and Jessi are very friendly with other pups, but Lily is a little skeptical of cats and is known to have a penchant for chasing chickens (though she's never caught one!). Lily can also be just a little shy around new people, but she warms up quickly and will be in your lap in no time! Both girls love to curl up on the couch with you and also enjoy walks (they have great leash manners) and car rides. Lily and Jessi have lived together for many years, and this dynamic duo is ready to find a forever home together. If you're interested in fostering or adopting, fill out an application on our website and we'll be in touch soon!

-----
IMPORTANT: To protect the health of our staff and volunteers, ARF is currently conducting adoptions by appointment only. Please see more information below.

-Contact Info:
Have questions first about the adoption process or a particular animal? Please click the Contact this Organization button.

-Ready to Adopt? Please visit www.animalrescuemobile.org to submit an adoption application, or click the Adopt Me button to request one via email.

-The Adoption Process:
An adoption application, veterinarian and/or personal reference, a home visit, and a $150 adoption fee are part of the process. All animals will be up to date on shots, microchipped, and spayed/neutered before adoption.

-Please Note:
Sponsors are needed to help ARF with the cost of vet care. If you would like to sponsor an ARF rescue, please click the Sponsor Me button. A sponsor donation of $50 will help cover the cost of a spay/neuter surgery. Plus, ARF is a non-profit organization and all donations are tax deductible.

animal.description:
Update Dec 14 - We just wanted to add a few things we've learned about Charlie since he came to stay with us. We think Charlie spent most of his time in his home and yard as he's very stressed when in new places. Once he's settled into a home he'll be comfortable, but it could take some time to get used to new noises and smells. Charlie is a simple guy and just needs some time in a private yard to play and with the help of a trainer learn to feel less anxious when on a walk. Currently he lunges and barks on walks when he sees a dog so needs to live somewhere he can be walked in quiet areas. 
He is very interested in squirrels and small critters so not cats for this guy! What Charlie needs is stability and a quiet environment with someone who can help him manage some of his anxiety. We will be looking for a detached home in a quiet area for this boy. 

_______________________________________________________________ 

Charlie is a handsome gentleman with a very serious face, but a silly personality. This big goof loves toys and happily prances around with them and will fetch...but not return it! Charlie is looking for a family with some dog experience, especially with larger dogs. He'd be happy to go for a walk and then snuggle on the couch!

Charlie was very stressed when he first arrived with us after his owner passed away. He's settled in now and we are so happy to see him so much more relaxed. Charlie was a dog who had a yard to take care of, so he does bark a bit if he hears unfamiliar noises, but we've already noticed he's much quieter. 

Charlie is dog reactive, especially when he's behind a fence. He will need to be the only dog in the home, and won't be visiting any dog parks. He walks well on leash, and while he will bark at other dogs, we've also seen this decrease since his arrival. Charlie has not been assessed with cats or small animals. 

Charlie is about 8/9 years old and in good health. 



Thank you for choosing to adopt an animal! 

Due to social distancing we will be doing the initial steps of our adoption process via email/phone and then arrange an appointment to come meet our cats. Please read the bios carefully to see if we have a cat that is a match for what you are looking for. You can then visit www.coquitlam.ca  to download an adoption application. Once complete and submitted we will be in touch!
*
*
*
All the animals that arrive at the Shelter are stray. The information that we have on the animals has been gathered since their arrival at the Shelter. and with the help of our volunteers. We do our best to assess the animals and disclose everything we know regarding health and temperament to interested adopters 

The application review process can take between 24-48 hours. The Shelter does NOT do same day adoptions. We do not ship animals or adopt outside of BC.

animal.description:
Hi world, my name is Omar!  I’m ready for a new beginning but before let me tell you my beginning, I had a rough start when I was first brought in with fly bitten ear wounds and drastically underweight.  I definitely am a ladies man and feel more comfortable with women than men at first, I will warm up to men after a little bit though.  I would do well in a ages 13+ home, no little ones!  I would be best suited where I am the only dog in the home but don’t worry, I got tons of love to give!   I am strong at first on a leash but after a couple minutes, I calm down and very easy to walk.  I love to play fetch but still working on bringing it back every time!  I love going to parks and going on runs!  I am a beach bum and love playing in the rolling waves, I am a snuggle addict and I love to give kisses!  I literally love to snuggle with you and I give kisses when you ask!  I may be a bigger boy but let’s face it, I just want to be your big baby!  With all this handsomeness, I have to add that I am quite smart too, I know quite a few commands and I catch on quickly!  Needless to say, I am all that and a furry tail that wags like crazy when I get a peanut butter treat!  I love hard and I’m ready to find my last furever home!  Inquire to meet me and I’ll mesmerize you with my dapper personality!  



You can visit Omar  at the Euclid Animal Shelter, 25100 Lakeland Blvd., Euclid, OH.  He has received his initial set of vaccinations except rabies and will be neutered before leaving the shelter. His adoption fee is $80. All of our dog kennels have indoor/outdoor runs so we cannot say with certainty if any of our dogs are housetrained.

“The Shelter will be changing some policies regarding adoptions and reclaims. Your Health as well as ours here at the Shelter is very important. We will be implementing all of the Health Department’s recommendations.
Reclaims and adoptions will be by appointment only. Please inquire via email or if you have any other questions call us at 
216-289-2057
Thank You
Ann Mills
Animal Control”

animal.description:
Born October 13, 2019, Draven is a male Australian Shepherd. Here is how is foster mom describes him: Draven is a young, fun loving guy! He loves walks/hikes, car rides and fellow canines. His happy place is with his canine buddies! Draven had a rough start. He can be unsure of humans. He uses his canine friends to show him which humans are worthy of his love and loyalty. For this reason, we will require Draven goes to a home with other dogs. Preferably dogs around his age, that want to play! Draven's ideal forever family will be patient with him and help him grow to be a confident and secure dog despite his early life. His foster mom says he's a goofy boy who will get mischievous with blankets and socks if left unattended with nothing to play with. He loves toys and chews! Draven is fully potty trained, and crate trained. Draven's forever home will require a secure 6 foot fence with adults or adults and children over 13, and no cats or small animals. Applications can be accessed at www.mikeyschance.com

All large and/or active dogs will require a full fenced (6ft) secure yard. 
No children under 5. 

Like all Mikey's Chance dogs, this dog will come to you from a foster home that has provided loving one-on-one attention, socialization and some basic training, as well as quality food and exercise. 

Applications can be found at www.mikeyschance.com and completed on a computer, tablet, and/or phone. Please note that adopters are not chosen on a first come, first served basis, but full consideration is given to the best fit for the dog AND the adopter. Applications can take up to 3 weeks to process. Application submission DOES NOT guarantee approval for adoption.

animal.description:
Meet Kira! Kira is a female chow/German shepherd mix born in December 2013. There are so many good things to say about Kira! She is adventurous, athletic, and a top notch mouse catcher! So no need for a cat in her forever home, especially since she is not fond of them. Kira is great with kids and loves every person she meets. She recently took her very first trip to a pet store and was VERY impressed. She rides great in a car and is well behaved in public. Kira’s ideal forever home would have a large fenced yard where she could explore when the weather is nice. She loves running through the yard chasing mice, bugs, and anything else that will run from her. She is especially skilled at catching treats mid-air. As far as dog friends, she could take them or leave them but does require proper introductions. If you think Kira could be the girl for you, fill out an application at www.mikeyschance.com. 

All large and/or active dogs will require a full fenced (6ft) secure yard. 
No children under 5. 

Like all Mikey's Chance dogs, this dog will come to you from a foster home that has provided loving one-on-one attention, socialization and some basic training, as well as quality food and exercise. 

Applications can be found at www.mikeyschance.com and completed on a computer, tablet, and/or phone. Please note that adopters are not chosen on a first come, first served basis, but full consideration is given to the best fit for the dog AND the adopter. Applications can take up to 3 weeks to process. Application submission DOES NOT guarantee approval for adoption.

animal.description:
Hewo der! My name is Speedy. I am a 5-year-old, male, Shephard mix weighing around 48 lbs. I am here because The
Cantu Foundation rescued me from a shelter in Tijuana. I wear diapers and I’m good with a leash on my wheels not on my collar. My background is a ruff one. I was found on the side of the road
after getting hit by a car! I was rescued by a shelter that lacked the resources to give me the medical attention I so desperately
needed. Instead, I was kept in a cage for more than 4 MONTHS! Thankfully The Cantu Foundation found me, stepped up, and took me in. I have the fight in me to walk again...I am currently getting
physical therapy and slowly getting better. Despite all of this, I am very chill. I love to be around my pack and go on walkies with my
pack. I am very affectionate, submissive, and I have a zest for life. There is so much more life has to offer, and I don’t want my set-back to get in the way of having the best life! I get all the compliments for being such a good boy (I try my best!). I get
along with other doggos and little hoomans. I love walkies and relaxing with my family. I pawmise I am the sweetest most loving
grateful doggo you will meet. I hope my journey starts with you! My perfect furever home would be one where I can hang out with my furever family/hooman. I can be left alone but I prefer to be with my hoomans. Little hoomans and other doggos would be just fine. Take me on walkies and car rides, I’ll be so happy! My
adoption fee is $200 and that includes spaying/neutering and vetting care. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here thecantufoundation.org/adopt

animal.description:
Meet Big Beautiful Billy

Billys DNA test says he is 75% American Staffordshire Terrier, 12.5% Boxer and 12.5% Hound. He is about 3 years old. Billy did not have a great start to his life, but then he came to AHS for his second chance at a wonderful loving life, the kind he deserves with the right family.

He is a very beautiful brindle color that people stop and notice. When people meet Billy they are amazed at just how sweet this big 85 pound boy is. Billy is microchipped and neutered, he gets along good with other dogs but we are not sure about cats.

He is good in the house and he is housebroken but please remember like with any new fur member of the family you must show him the ropes, let him know where the door is and let him get acquainted with his new surroundings. You will need to learn HIS signs of letting you know when he has to go out and that, like most things will take patients, commitment and time.

Billy is a big boy and he loves to play fetch and will bring it back to you and drop it at your feet but if you wait too long to throw that toy he will jump up and try to get it. That being said I would not recommend that he play fetch with very small children as he is very big and powerful and could possibly knock them over with his excitement.

He does sit, lay down and offer either paw on command when he is at home and in a calm environment. He needs some work on that when he is out though as he gets very excited to be out playing. He is a bit nervous about cars that drive by when walking and that may have something to do with his past, he will just need love and trust and work with that so that he knows his new home and family will always keep him safe.

He needs some work with his car rides, he does get a bit anxious when he is in the car and will bark. A kennel is recommended for car rides and some work on that. He also needs leash training, he is a big powerful boy and tends to pull on his leash as he does not know any better. He needs someone to teach him the proper way to walk on one. He likes the Costco Signature lamb rice and Veggie food and it seems to do well with him.

Once he gets settled in and is comfortable with you if you put his dog bed by your bed he will sleep there and in the morning he may ask to join you for a little morning hug.

Because Billy is a HIGHLY ACTIVE boy the best person/couple/family suited for him must also be very active. Long walks, runs, hiking will be very beneficial for him. A fenced yard is required for this boy so he has a place to run when hes home.

If you are interested in meeting this big beautiful boy please fill out a statement of interest at http://alternative-humane-society.com

LETS GET BILLY-HOME FOR THE HOLIDAYS

animal.description:
Are you looking for a handsome, playful and big chunk of  "goofball" that is a diamond in the rough ? If you are a confident dog owner, that has lots of  experience with dog training, then I may be your man!  My name is King and I want to be the King of your heart! 

My story is a bit of a mystery, but I am a Husky mix and my new friends at HRAAD believe I am around 1 year old at about 85 pounds right now. 

The previous humans in my life didn't expose me to a-lot of training, so I would do best in a home with no other dogs or children. I really need someone that has experience in large breeds specifically Husky/Malamutes and strong skills in socialization/training. Beautiful relationships sometimes take time. I need someone who will invest the time to come to the shelter and get to know me and build my trust, which means there will need to be multiple supervised meet and greets after an application is approved.

What are some of my favorite things? I thought you would never ask! While some might say, "raindrops on roses, and whiskers of kittens" my love cup is filled with toys, and going on walks! If you are looking for some entertainment, I promise to give you a daily show with a front row seat to my 85lb puppyish antics playing with my toys, (I just might not want to share them sometimes.

King has grown so much during his time at here at HRAAD, and is one of our staff's favorites. He has learned leash manners and continues to bring us joy with his playfulness and goofy demeanor. With that being said, King has shown reactive behaviors when going to the vet as well as guarding his toys and food. King is also very excitable, and needs more work on his jumping, and has nipped someone when he was overly excited. For these reasons, King needs to go to a highly experienced dog owner that is willing to continue training.

Will you take me home and give the attention and training I need to become a very good BIG boy? 

If you are interested in adopting me, all you have to do is submit an adoption application, which can be found on our website at www.hoodriveradoptadog.org

Once your submitted application has been approved,  my adoption counselor will be in contact to discuss the next steps, answer any questions and to schedule a meet and greet.

My adoption fee is $300

IN VERMONT / IN NEED OF LOCAL FOSTER OR ADOPTER/ AVAILABLE FOR FOSTER TO ADOPT FOR LOCAL ADOPTERS

Meet Ryder! Here is his video from being rescued to playing in the grass!

https://youtu.be/Y9KW4Yu3kqM

Ryder is 15 months-old (DOB 7-21-19), male, 55 lbs., vetted, is or will be neutered, and micro-chipped. Ryder fka Bubba was an Owner Surrender in NC who was very selfless in giving him up to a rescue where he could have a happier life. He is a good boy who is learning about the world. Ryder is potty trained, crate trained, has meduim+ energy, walks well on a leash, and know Sit, Stay, Wait, and Leave it. He loves his toys and blankets! Ryder's ideal home would be active, have Intermediate experience and a be strong and confident leader to provide him structure and experienced input, with or without another dog, no cats (seems to have a prey drive toward yard animals), be more rural and outside of an overstimulating city life! Since Ryder is still a toddler that has a short attention span and uses his mouth to express himself we would not recommend small children. Stay tuned as Ryder is a new rescue!

If you are interested in fostering or adopting Ryder please fill out an Application at

www.Passion-4-Paws.org

(please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out his Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

animal.description:
***ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS***

Joker is a 1-2 year old male Shepherd/Doberman type mix who arrived from Texas.  He has been working on some puppy behaviors and is now ready to find a home to continue his training!  Joker is approximately 70-75 pounds and is considered full grown.

Joker is a bit exuberant when meeting pups, but given proper introductions, he does well with all those he has met!  Joker does best with medium/large pups as he loves to wrestle and roughhouse and can be too much for smaller pups.  Joker is far too interested in cats and should have a home without.

Joker is excited to meet new people and has been working hard on improving his manners.  Occasionally he will still jump up.  He still needs practice on his leash walking skills, but his foster has been working with him and he’s improving.

Joker is kennel trained and believed to be house trained as he hasn’t had any accidents in his foster home.  Joker loves to have his stuffed kong or bone in his kennel to help him pass the time when his foster is at work. Joker loves to play with toys, although he can make short work out of the stuffed ones!  Joker has been working hard on his basic obedience and is treat motivated – his new family should expect to continue working on his commands to help him continue to learn to be a well-mannered boy!

Joker is vet checked, started on vaccinations, heartworm tested negative, microchipped and neutered.  He is current on his flea/tick/heartworm/deworming preventatives.  Joker’s adoption donation fee is $300.00

We realize that people are looking for a predominant breed or breed mixture, but visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at the predominant breed or breed mix.  We encourage you to select your new companion by considering each dog's individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on a breed label that is only a guess.

If you're interested in adopting, please visit our main website at www.sarahstreasuresrescue.net for adoption information and our application!

animal.description:
Brady is 1 yr, 5 mos old, male, hound mix, about 65 lbs. Brady was a MUCH loved dog by his previous owner and it broke their heart to have to bring him back to us but they are unexpectedly returning to their home overseas and are unable to take Brady with them. Brady was obviously treasured by his previous owner as evidenced by the huge trove of items that he also came to us with and that will go out with him to his approved adopter. You can tell Brady was very loved indeed. Now he is a high energy hound boy, so don't think you can just park him in a back yard as we will only adopt him to a home where he will be a member of the family, inside, like he was with his previous owner. He is housetrained and we don't often get to write that about our big hounds. He is great with other dogs, would be a superb running partner for someone as well. And just so you know Brady has been used to eating high quality food, so no junky cheapo food for him - his owner even dehydrated meat and the like for him for natural snacks. Only restriction is he does not seem to be about children so no children please.
ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

animal.description:
*****************************************************************
PLEASE READ THOROUGHLY BEFORE INQUIRING
*****************************************************************

--ABOUT COCO--
Coco is a Diamond in the Ruff! Interested adopters should visit her page at www.buddydoghs.org/coco to view her story, adopter requirements, and more photos and videos!

Key Note
-4-year old spayed female.
-Unknown breed mix.
-42 pounds and a healthy weight.
-Surrendered by family to a rescue in Puerto Rico when they were moving and could not take her.
-Experience with dogs needed.
-No apartments, multi-family homes, or cities.
-Needs a quiet neighborhood with few to no other dogs.
-No electric/invisible fences; would worsen her reactivity.
-Needs adult only (18+) home.
-Should be an only pet; may eventually be able to live with another dog with training.
-No more than 8 hours alone a day; will need a potty and play break.
-Medium-high energy; eager to play and explore.
-Very dog selective; can befriend very tolerant and non-confrontational dogs.
-Intelligent and eager to learn; food motivated.
-Strong on leash but good with no-pull harness.
-Housebroken and knows sit and paw.
-Guards favorite toys/food from people but has been quickly improving with training.
-Behavioral training for reactivity recommended.

--THE ADOPTION PROCESS--
If you are interested in adopting this animal, please submit an online application. Applications will be reviewed as received. If in our opinion a pet is a good candidate for you, an adoption counselor will contact you to schedule a zoom chat. If you do not hear from us it simply means either the animal has been adopted or we have not received the right pet for you. The application process is at no charge to you and only needs to be completed once as all applications will be kept on file.

Online applications can be found here: www.buddydoghs.com/forms

Check out our FAQ for answers to most questions here: www.buddydoghs.com/faq

Adopters must be at least 21 years of age and a Massachusetts resident.

animal.description:
Tough times never last, but tough dogs do! With a name like Noodle, you might assume that life has been easy for this little fella, but when he came to Paws in the City, he was in bad shape. With heartworms, a hernia and bad teeth he was feeling pretty lousy. Noodle was also starving, and he still needs to gain some weight! Now that all of his medical needs have been met, and he's got a steady source of food, Noodle needs LOVE!

Noodle is a 10-year-old, 13 lb. Chihuahua mix. He's shy at first, but once he gets to know you, he's very affectionate! Noodle would be a great BFF. He likes other dogs and has been enjoying the company of his foster brothers. Noodle is also very eager to please, and he learns quickly. He would love someone to teach him some new commands. When Noodle naps, he loves to snuggle up with his stuffed toy Valentine's heart.

Noodle is working on his leash skills and crate training. We suspect he had never walked on a leash before coming to PITC. Noodle is also learning that he no longer has to scrounge for food and will now receive a daily supply. He's also discovered a new favorite food, cottage cheese!! Noodle would do best in a home without children.

For adoption information or to complete an application, please go to: http://www.pawsinthecity.org/adopt.htm

References and a home visit are required for all adoptions.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 8/31/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Gypsy was surrendered by her owners directly to rescue
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Gypsy was spayed on 9/22/20 and is now ready for her forever home. GYPSY WILL NOT BE ADOPTED TO A FIRST TIME DOG OWNER.
Weight: 37 lbs
Height: 18 in
Spayed/Neutered: No

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Gypsy needs an owner experienced with rescue dogs. She has never lived in a home and is just beginning to learn what human kindness means. Gypsy's entire life has been lived in a feral, outdoor colony. She has come a long way in a short time in rescue, but is very much a work in progress. She would be okay with other dogs in the home, but does not require them. Gypsy is not well suited to a home with younger children.

Gypsy's ideal owner has rescued dogs and has experience with dogs that are undersocialized and/or haven't had a lot of life experiences. They are committed to slowly and patiently teaching her how to be a dog.

What is my personality like? Gypsy has lived her entire life as part of a feral dog colony. She was loved and fed by her owners, but human interaction was not part of life. Gypsy was much loved as a young dog, perhaps even living inside the house; but then as more and more dogs came (some even her puppies), she and her fellow canines were thrown outside. Gypsy became the leader, not a role she wanted, but a role she was put into and needed to fill. It was up to her to keep the pack safe and it was a lot of pressure on her. There was never enough resources, never enough food, never enough water, never enough shelter. Gypsy had to make had choices and she had to keep 17 dogs from fighting. She had to grow up faster than any pup should have to.

Not that the pressure if off, Gypsy simply wants to be the best companion dog she can be. She shows you this by wanting to be with you. That life was had. Now that she no longer has to worry Gypsy can just relax. But she wants to follow. Gypsy knows and is comfortable living with other dogs. Gypsy has slowly begun to learn the routine of crating, feeding, humans, etc. since arriving in rescue on 8/31/20.

Gypsy's caregivers describe her as a sweet girl who will sit at your feet and does not want to be ignored. It is important to remember this is the perspective of individuals Gypsy has known and been building trust with for several months. She will do this with her new home - but it will take some time. Gypsy is an alpha dog. She will hump her friends / siblings / family from the feral colony to show her dominance. She does fine with other dogs, but does not need another dog in the home.

Leash walking is a skill that we have been slowly working on with Gypsy. She is timid on a leash, which is not surprising given that she's never been on one before. She has learned the routine of being crated, but does not like when other dogs walk by her crate and will bark and growl at them. In general, Gypsy does best being introduced to dogs in open spaces. If another dog is behind a fence, Gypsy will just bark at them. She didn't have a lot of boundaries in her feral colony days and we suspect that contributes to this behavior.

Gypsy is still very much a work in progress, but has come a long way and has a ton of potential.

How do I act when I first meet new people?

Other tips and tidbits: Gypsy's estimated birthday is 9/1/2016

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

Banner while initially shy and skittish has done a complete 180 and is a fun, loving, attention seeking pup who enjoys very much the human company he has been desperately craving. Despite his meager beginnings, he is great on leash, rides well in the car, gets along with all sizes of dogs and has been great with all humans he has met so far. Banner is so happy be indoors you will often find him snoozing away and in such a deep sleep that he snores. animal.description:
1-16-2021: Harvey is doing GREAT!! He's gained 8lbs and just had his surgery and new blood work. He's so much stronger and happier now. He can do 2 flights of stairs and is working hard on his house training. He is one of the sweetest dogs I have ever met. He is great with other dogs and cat safe. I am looking for a Foster to Adopt home that can help continue his heartworm slow kill and spoil him rotten. You must have a safe fenced in yard.

11-3: I was contacted about a Setter in a shelter in Southern Illinois the end of October. Thanks to my old rescue friend Kathy, we got Harvey on a transport to Chicago on 11-5. I thought perhaps he was a senior in the first photos I saw of him and I knew he was thin. Upon arrival hew was weak, emaciated and defeated looking. Thankfully my vet had booked an appointment for us with his arrival and started him on IV fluids right away. They also shaved off most of the terrible matting all over his body. Harvey was also covered in fleas and he had a very low heart beat called Bradycardia. Dr. John and I both agreed we would be shocked if he didn't have heartworms. After his blood was drawn and a B12 injection, Harvey and I headed home for his spa treatment. After the flea shampoo, I got him started on intestinal dewormer and gave him a good meal that also included heartguard and antibiotics. He ate very well thankfully. Blood work the next day showed he was indeed heartworm positive and he also had hookworms and had elevated white blood cells, neutrophils and lymphocytes and he also has a tick borne disease called Rocky Mountain spotted fever. The next morning Harvey was feeling so much better. He was holding his head up and his eyes weren't so sunken in. He continued to eat better and also stated trotting around my yard. Later that morning he moved to foster care and spent the weekend at their lake home with more TLC and lots more food. Harvey is currently being treated with our heartworm slow kill program and we will take our time building him up before he is neutered. He came in weighing 37lbs and needs to gain at least 15-20lbs. We aren't sure of his age- but estimate he could be 9- 12 years old and is partially deaf. 11-16: After a week in care- Harvey is doing tremendously well. He has lots more energy and lots more spunk. We now believe he is at the younger side of his age estimate. We are actively looking for a Foster to Adopt home for him in the Chicago area that can help us continue his treatment. If you would like to help out, please message me here or call Lisa at 630-694-1359.

animal.description:
Castle was originally transferred to us from Detroit Animal Care and Control, where he was found as a stray. Castle was fearful and shut down when he first arrived at THS. He is currently residing in a foster home where he has made incredible progress! 

His foster reports that he is housebroken, and working on crate training! Castles favorite time of the day, Breakfast and dinner! As soon as he wakes up in the morning, he is dancing around until his breakfast is served. Castle is slowly learning that the world is a not-so-scary place after all. Castle used to walk off the side of the trail to avoid new people walking by. But after just a few short months, Castle is now able to keep calm and walk right next to his foster mom on walks. Although he is still working on his confidence when passing loud noises, Castle receives compliments on his excellent leash walking skills! What's better than a walk through the park? Obviously, the car ride home! Castle makes a wonderful copilot and enjoys watching the world pass by through the window. 

During the day he prefers to lounge around and will rotate from napping on his dog bed, to the couch, to the bed. When he first arrived to his fosters home, he did not have a clue what toys were, or how to play with them. Although he still has yet to play with toys, he has begun to chew on bones! With a calm household and a patient family, Castle should be able to continue to make great progress and learn how to become a happy and confident dog. Adopters should consult with a trainer to continue to help Castle make progress after adoption as well. 

Castle is currently residing in a foster home with another dog, and seems to enjoy the company! He takes time to warm up to people, and will initially go to his "safe place" (foster moms room) when guests first arrive. After the activity settles down, he will come back out and join everyone. Although he enjoys watching from afar, this is great progress for Castle as he used to avoid strangers altogether. 

Castle was recently treated for heartworm disease and will need to go home with a year of heartworm prevention medication. THS requires all adopters of heartworm positive dogs to purchase a 1 year supply of heartworm preventative at the time of adoption.

Email foster@toledohumane.org if you are interested in adopting!

Is the sweetest and smartest dog I have met in a while.

That being said, he needs a very dog experienced person and a woman or women humans as his forever family. The male in his life was abusive. Fetch was forced to live outdoors for at least 11 months of the year for his entire 5 years. He is so happy to be indoors and warm has a cozy bed and real food.

Fetch needs a VERY dog, savvy WOMAN. perhaps someone who has adopted rescued dogs or understands the abused dog. Though his life was miserable, and he was so scared when he arrived, it took just a week to gain his trust. Fetch needs someone who will spend a lot of time just talking to him, coaxing him with healthy treats, and being patient. Once he decides he trusts you, he becomes your best friend HEART and SOUL. Fetch is a very special boy. He loves to be held, sleep close, and go everywhere you go. When properly introduced to a new woman, and having that individual give him a treat he will do well with them. He can pick out an untrustworthy person from 100 yards and warn you they need to keep their distance, heed that warning. He is spot on. Fetch really frieks out with men so we have learned, NO males. Period. He fears men's feet, so we assume he was kicked.

Fetch loves to go for walks, but the city life overwhelms him. Mostly due to having been locked in a yard. He has leash aggression so it's best to walk him on trials and when there is a dog on a lead in the distance, take him away from the oncoming dog. Fetch is leash trained and he does love his walks, so it would be nice if you are also a long-distance walker and will give this boy the physical and mental stimulation he needs. Fetch would do best in a more rural area for walking, or smaller town.

Fetch was so named because he loves to run the length of a yard to fetch a ball and return it. We have a massive yard here, the likes of which he has never seen and he loves to run it. He is getting into great physical shape.

Fetch is being fed a raw diet and Human Grade dog food. We will educate his adopters on Canine Nutrition and species-specific foods.

To fill out an application to adopt Please use this link, You will need a computer to complete as cell phones will drop the application. Fetch has a $650.00 adoption fee. All fees are recycled to save more dogs

http://rompinpawsrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/

The site will ask you to create a password and will send you an email. For ease of use, just use the password they create for you and save that password. This will ensure you have access and can fill out the application.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.If you are viewing this dog on a website other than BFPA.org, please go directly to
our website for more information on adoption requirements and specifics for this dog.
Websites such as Petfinder and Adopt-A-Pet may not show all the information that we
have listed.
FOSTER PARENT COMMENTS: Captain is very friendly toward other people and loves everyone he meets. He has a full body wag when he meets people and dances around for the first ten minutes before calming down for cuddles and kisses!
He gets along with dogs and has done well in doggy day care. He likes to play and
is always ready to play with a flirt pole! With other dogs, he uses his whole body to
play and this means he needs playmates that can keep up with his energy.
If he lives with another dog, they will need to have the same style of play. He could
be a perfect only or first dog too!
He is not aggressive with toys or bones but he definitely likes to make them all his. We
do not know how he would do with cats.
He does really well with older children...11 and over. Due to his size and energy
level, he would probably be a bit much for younger children.
Captain is probably too large and vocal for apartment living. He is very alert to noises
and will bark if he sees someone through the window. At that point, if he is sent to
another room (yes, he listens to commands to exit the room/enter the crate etc) he will
calm down.
He is fully house and crate trained. He sleeps on his bed at night next to the foster's
bed. He is crated only when the foster is away for work. He is comfortable and
familiar with the crate and is smart enough to know that his dad will come back. He
does not whine when the foster parent is away and passes time on his own like a
champ. He is a high energy, big puppy.
Captain gets two 30 minute walks per day as the foster is working on the leash walking.
In addition to this, the foster uses a flirt pole and tug toys to play and further provide
exercise as Captain is getting shredded preparing for adoption day! When he has been
exercised by playing, walking or jogging, he turns into a snuggler. But when he lacks
exercise, his behavior will reflect that he needs exercise. A fenced yard for playing
and running is great, but he does very well with two walks a day or one walk and
playtime with other dogs/toys outdoors.

Captain's foster has worked with him on basic training and he has learned several
commands. He is very, VERY smart and is food motivated which helps with
training. The foster was able to teach him two tricks in one day! He is young and so
full of life. His happiness is contagious especially when he is carrying around his bone
with his behind wiggling from his tail wagging so hard! Captain is the sweetest dog
who has never met a stranger and who will be a loyal family member. He will be
ready and by your side for any adventure you have planned! He loves humans
and absolutely loves to give kisses. Could he give one to you??
EVERY DOG HAS A STORY: Captain was originally found as a stray and taken to
Wake County Animal Shelter. He was adopted very quickly into a home with
another dog. The older dog in the home had issues with him as he got to be a bigger
dog and needed to be rehomed.
Some of the information contained in this biography includes approximations based
on our expertise and is not guaranteed.

application by copying and pasting this link in a new browser

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

If you are viewing this dog on a website other than BFPA.org, please go directly to our website for more information on adoption requirements and specifics for this dog. PLEASE COMPLETE AN APPLICATION AT BFPA.ORG IF INTERESTED!

Melanie is a Chihuahua mix about 10 years old. She is currently 9 pounds but will not weigh more then 10-11 pounds. She will make a wonderful companion for an older person or a younger couch tater. She is pretty low maintenance, comical , she only wants to be warm and fed. Her true happiness would be on the couch with her person.

Melanie was rescued on the side of the road. She weighed almost 7 lbs and was skin and bones. Her hide was a field of seed tics. Her eyes were so cloudy we doubted her eyesight. This was a sad, neglected, abandoned pup. She had major trust issues, not wanting you to scoop her up. We, frankly, were unsure she'd recover. The first weeks we just bathed and fed her and let her sleep. She surprised us. She looks like a dog now. She gleefully tears out the back door with the other dogs. Her recovery has been remarkable.

She is timid but is better once she settles in and gets to know you. She still doesn't really like being picked up but will follow you around the house. She gets along with my 2 dogs, but I think she'd be happier as an only dog. Melanie does OK with cats. She has been around a 4 and 6 year old child alot, she is aware they are there but has no interest in them. She's not a dog to be adopted as a child's pet.

She's quiet unless there is a visitor. Then, she lets you know you have company. She is housebroken but as an older dog, the owner must be diligent in taking her out. She has been left for 6 hours before without a potty break. She sleeps through the night easily in her crate in the den. She is crate trained with no complaint. She must be placed in the crate. She may have spent too much time crated in her past, so is not eager to walk into the crate.

Melanie has a low level of energy. She is amazingly quick when she wants to be. A fenced yard is nice, but not a necessity. We have not been leash walking Melanie but her new family would have to work with her on this. She will come when you call her and follow you. Picking her up is not her favorite thing, but if you do, she is calm and quiet in your arms.

Melanie is currently diabetic and requires insulin shots twice daily. We're not sure if this is a lifelong condition, but it may be. This is not a cuddly wet kisses kind of small dog. This is an observant older companion that stays by your side, wants to be in the room you are in. Her favorite pastime is waiting on her next meal and napping on the couch with me. Melanie is looking for her forever home that will give her all the love and security she deserves after a rough start to her life.

Some of the information contained in this biography includes approximations based on our expertise and is not guaranteed.

Applicants must live a reasonable distance from Cary NC as our dogs must be seen by a BFPA veterinarian for all medical care prior to adoptions being finalized. Our foster guardians deliver dogs to their new homes for adoption trials and we do home visits to finalize all adoptions. We therefore require applicants to live within a reasonable drive of Cary NC.

Available for Adoption in NJ & PA


This is Elsa. She is about a year and half old and a petite lady at 40 lbs. Elsa had a rough start to her short life, she and her sister came into the shelter as strays as young pups and they stayed in the shelter for quite a few months until a caring foster stepped up to take them out of the shelter and show them what life with a loving family is all about.

She is shy with humans and has been working really hard to learn to trust people. She has been with her current foster for a few months now and is learning that humans can be pretty cool.

Elsa is looking for a family that is willing to be patient with her and show her that she is loved and worth the wait. We promise you that if you give her a chance, she will be the perfect companion. She enjoys long walks, peanut butter pretzels and playing with her canine foster sister. Naps and snuggles on the sofa next to her trusted human is her most favorite activity of all.

Elsa is crate trained and house trained. We think a household with a canine sister or brother or two would be amazing-in fact, only homes with a canine sibling will be considered for Elsa. Kids are ok but we feel not younger then 10 would be best.  We are not sure about cats but think a fenced in yard would be perfect.

Elsa is UTD on everything, microchipped and spayed and would love an opportunity to find her forever family. If you think your home would be a good fit for our sweet Elsa, please consider applying @ https://www.emailmeform.com/builder/form/ICY0zLb5eMAfRd8dptd7

Everyone meet Hagrid, he is a 3-4 year old pit bull mix that weighs about 55 lbs. He is kennel trained, house trained, and good with dogs and cats. He is in a foster home with smaller dogs right now and loves all the small dogs he meets and has been good with bigger dogs but can be slightly dominant. He doesn't have an aggressive bone in his body, he loves all people. He loves to sleep at night in the bed with his people or sleeping in a dog bed in the room with you. He is the sweetest dog you will ever meet, he loves to cuddle on the couch and is very chill. He is heart worm positive but has received treatment and the rescue will pay for treatment until he is negative. He needs a large fenced in yard as he hates to use the bathroom on a leash and loves to run in a yard! Please consider giving this sweet baby his forever home 

If you are interested in giving Hagrid a forever home, please visit the link below to fill out an application! http://fureverafterrescue.org/adoption-application.html It is best to submit an application through a computer. We have experienced some problems when applications have been submitted using a mobile device. *When you submit the application, you are not obligated to adopt however it does reserve for you the opportunity to adopt that particular animal. We review them on a first come first served basis. If your application is approved, we will contact you and allow you the opportunity to adopt. If you choose not to adopt, we will contact the next approved applicant. If you have any questions or difficulties, please contact us and we will be glad to help!
