animal.description:
~~~~~
Buck is a beagle/terrier shep mix.  He weighs about 40 pounds  He is 1-1.5 years old. Good with all and very sweet!
 He is a real sweet pea- loves to cuddle on the sofa   loves. a  nice walk in the yard or neighborhood - sweet on kids. 
His foster mum says every time that she looks at him , it's like looking at a toddler with a baseball cap toddling around in the kennel yard!   Interested in adopting ?? Fill an application at LittleRhodyRescue.com ! 

~~~~~


Due to Covid-19 concerns, we are not planning any public adoption events. If you are pre approved , we will call to set up an appointment to come and meet the dog and potentially take them home. It is by appointment only- 
Dogs will be brought into the outdoor kennel for you to meet and make your decision. MASKS WILL BE MANDATORY to maintain EVERYONE'S safety  NO EXCEPTIONS PLEASE !! Unless otherwise noted, the puppies and dogs listed will arrive on Saturday, November 7th, 2020 .
Please follow this link to fill out an application. It is step one in adopting a pup from our rescue.
http://littlerhodyrescue.com/adoption-application/ 

*Filling an application does not guarantee you as the adopter. All applicant's references will be called. PLEASE call your veterinarian and personal references and allow consent to speaking with us ! 
We cannot process your application otherwise. Failure will put your application in 'Limbo"  
We process applications as they arrive. The first approved applicant will be called and the pup taken off of Petfinder. We do not have the man/ woman power to all all other applicants to advise them. 
IF there s another dog that you are interested in as well, please list at the top of the application and we will enter your application for that pup if the first choice has been adopted. 

THANK YOU !!! You are giving a first rate dog a second chance....By adopting! 

***** SADLY , we need to put this in print: THIS IS A RESCUE DOG. We do NOT know their birthday / age.  (unless other wise noted)  
More often than not, OUR TEAM  has saved them from euthanasia in Southern shelters. 
We do not know any more than our Veterinarians offer to us. 
 We often have them in kennels, and utilize crate training.  House training status is often NOT KNOWN. 
Prior Health, estimated weight  (as an adult), breed (Including the parents' breed , size or mix)   and some health concerns are  NOT KNOWN unless our veterinarians discover it and offer the information to us.   Again, these are strays and turn ins from all over the country. They do NOT come with labels; nor guarantees. 

Characteristics and disposition can and will evolve with time.
YOU the adopter are responsible to train and keep up to date on vaccines and preventatives.  
YOU the adopter are responsible for taking care of this new member of your family. 
 *************

****
Our adoption fees are $ 600. This fee includes the transportation of the pet from one of the organizations that we work with in TX, LA or TN. Before joining us in RI all dogs are: spayed/neutered, microchipped, up to date on age-appropriate vaccines, and on de-wormers, flea/tick and heartworm prevention. In addition, all adults (6 months +) are heartworm tested and MUST be negative for both heartworm and microfilaria before transport. 

In addition to the above, all dogs must have a Certificate of Veterinary Inspection and be deemed healthy per USDA law in order to travel. Once they have been certified they are then transported via USDA transport services only, which is required by law. 
 We  sometimes don't understand how bad the situation is for these pups and dogs in southern states.  Many people in the south don't spay or neuter their pets as we do here. Subsequently, there are thousands of beautiful , worthy pups and dogs, kittens and cats  that are dumped, shot, abandoned, brought into shelters, neglected, abused and abandoned.  We step in , tend to their veterinary needs. As you can see above, we never fail to properly spay and neuter. Everything is done with the  caring , capable hands of our veterinarians to get them healthy and ready to place them for adoption. That's when we put the demand for family- friendly pets with the supply ..... 

Give a first rate dog a second chance!!!! ADOPT! 


Keep in mind that we also offer a two week return policy for the return of a healthy dog that includes a full refund. We want to make sure that the adoption is a perfect fit for both you and the dog.

If you would like more information about adopting please select "More About Little Rhody Rescue" where you will also find our online application if you'd like to proceed with the adoption process. Thank you!

Emma Jean is a spunky little lady of approximately 12 years and 22 lb.. She loves everyone she meets. She would do best in a home with small dogs or bigger dogs who are a little older and less playful. She would also be fine with cats as she ignores other pets.Emma has met some kids and seems fine, but we would suggest older kids just because she's a senior girl.
Emma Jean is very laid back and is just happy to be with her human. She loves to nap but is also always up for a walk and even a hike!
Emma does have one eye that does not have sight, but it doesn't seem to bother her. She's getting some eye lubricant drops daily. She is also slightly hard of hearing but that just means her naps are interrupted less! She truly is the sweetest little girl.
Emma Jean needs a family that is home more often because she does have accidents when left for more than 6 hours. However, she is house-trained if taken out more often--understandable! She is not fond of a crate or being locked in one room. She wants to be with her humans.Emma Jean is microchipped, spayed, up-to-date on vaccines and heartworm negative. To find out more about Emma Jean, contact her foster mom, Gloria, at 706-541-2052. Emma's adoption fee is $225.00 & she is in Augusta, GA.

NOTE: Submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston, since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.

Please use the foster momma or dad's contact information above for questions.
The process always begins with an application which can be found at The Boston Terrier Rescue of East Tennessee website
Note that in most cases, we do not adopt to families with small children, e.g., 'under 6,' as a precaution to the child's safety and the dog's safety. In some cases with larger Boston mixes or other dogs, we do make exceptions. Please ask the foster momma.
We prefer to place dogs within driving distance of where they are being fostered. If someone from outside the local area is approved for adoption, they must be willing to personally drive/fly to get the dog. The East Coast division (NC/SC/VA/MD/DC) does have special transport capabilties for their kids. Ask them.
Also, submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.

animal.description:
Sylvia is a young dog with an unknown past. We rescued her from a rural shelter. Her life before that is a mystery. She came to us anxious and fearful of normal, everyday things like going outside and going for car rides. In the last month that she's been with us, Sylvia has come a long way! Her foster family sees progress with her every week! She is affectionate and loving towards her foster family and enjoys spending time at their sides as they work or do their online schooling. Sylvia is now much more comfortable going outside and even runs around a bit! Her foster family has even seen her natural border collie running/herding moves a couple of times! She's still a bit skittish, but she has definitely become more relaxed in her foster home. Sylvia's anxiety is improving, but she is still a work in progress. Her foster family continues to work with her with the everyday things, and her forever family would need to be prepared to continue to work with her. We are looking for an experienced dog owner without small kids and without other dogs.

We are currently looking for an experienced dog owner that can continue to work with Sylvia on her issues. She is probably better as an only dog. If you really want to make a difference with a rescue and have the time to work with Sylvia, she is making great strides already, and is a young girl with so much potential!
_________________________________________________________________________
Adoption Donation for Sylvia is $ 425.00

WANT TO MEET Sylvia

The first step would be for you to go to our website at www.aear.org and then to the ""Adopting a Pet"" page to read about our Adoption Process which will answer many of your questions and then to fill out an Adoption Application.

Also, please visit our very active Facebook Page for updates on Sylvia and our other adoptable pets with AEAR - www.facebook.com/aear.org

animal.description:
COURTSEY LISTING FOR STREET DOG HERO - APPLY HERE: https://www.streetdoghero.org/benson

Meet Benson! This handsome boy is about 3.5 years old and 70 lbs of love! Benson loves nothing more than to feel safe and snuggle on the couch or lounge around with his humans. He is very sweet and gives a lot of love! Benson is great with humans (kids 10+ ok too) and loves to meet new people. He’s very smart and quick to learn new tricks like high five, paw, stay, sit and lay. He’s also crate and potty trained! Benson was not properly trained or introduced to other animals early on in his life, so he has a high prey drive. We are working with a trainer in Eugene, OR who is helping him appropriately react to other animals. However, due to his reactivity, he will need a home where he is the only pet and has a very secure (6ft +) and solid fenced yard (no chain link or other see through fences). Benson has learned a communication system built on rewards and positive verbal markers. This system can be used to continue to develop and nurture his self confidence. Much of his dog reactivity is rooted in a lack of feeling safe. To thrive he will need a strong leader to advocate for him, manage his occasional outbursts of leash reactivity (towards cats/dogs) and to protect him from harm. His ideal match is someone mentally alert enough and physically strong enough to correct and redirect him when he fails to control his impulses. He enjoys affection and praise which can be used as a form of reward. Due to Benson's strength and size, a muzzle should always be worn when out in public. He does have mild separation anxiety and is more comfortable when his human is with him. He is crate trained which can be used at times when he must be left alone. He has shown no signs of human aggression or resource guarding but he seems to have had previous success grabbing the leash away from his handler when overstimulated or frustrated. Another reason a muzzle is ideal for leash walking or being on leash in public. Benson needs a family or best friend who can manage his size and strength, and is ok with him staying at home or playing in the yard (and being managed appropriately). He is not for someone looking for a running or walking partner, or someone that wants to take their dog out to the breweries. He is a sweet human bonded dog that wants to be by your side at home, and will reward you with lots of snuggles and kisses. Benson's trainer has graciously offered to help any potential adopter with transitioning Benson into his new home and provide support. Benson has had a tremendously difficult life but he is ready to find love and support in a family who loves him. Benson was rescued from a shelter in Los Angeles, CA and is being fostered in Eugene, OR. Will you be his hero?

APPLY ONLINE HERE: https://www.streetdoghero.org/benson

He sometimes gets so obsessed with a toy, he'll actually "guard" it and can get snappy about it.  Due to his trust issues and resource guarding tendencies, he would do best in a home with an experienced human, and no small children.  He's turning into quite the handsome fellow of a nice, medium size!  Anyone interested in Elroy should plan on coming out to spend time with him several times, to really get to know him. 
 Come check out Elroy and our other dogs available for adoption at 2650 Washington Blvd, Crescent City, CA 95531.

animal.description:
****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if this puppy is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing.****

Name: Blue Eyes

Age: 6 years

Current Weight: 32 lbs

Rescued from: Texas

Health: up to date with required vaccinations, spayed, microchipped, Spine issue (is on pain meds to manage it but gets around fine!), Heartworm positive (SNARR covering treatment)

Adoption fee: $300

Meet Blue Eyes!  This little compact gal is fun loving, happy and ready for her next adventure. Blue eyes suffered a spinal injury that's inoperable, but is manageable with pain meds and does not slow her down one bit. She's never met a stranger and greets everyone she meets with whole body wiggles. Pictures don't do this girl justice..... when you see her you can't help but smile.  She has so much love to give and needs a family to spoil her rotten. Blue Eyes would not do well in an apartment. 

From Blue Eyes' foster mom: Blue Eyes is a really great, low maintenance dog! She’s very friendly and loves to ask for pets and treats from the humans! It’s hard to say no to her wiggling, waggling tail! Blue Eyes has a spinal injury that is well maintained with medication and does not slow her down, she gets excited for her walks when she sees her leash and sometimes likes to play with her ball. Blue Eyes is well house trained and knows basic commands. She walks well on her leash! This pretty girl is smaller than her pictures let on and she enjoys laying near her humans. Blue Eyes would do best in a quiet, relaxed home without children.

To apply to adopt Blue Eyes, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

Hi I’m Spencer. My foster parents call me “Pencie” for short. I’m a 6-7 month old Great Dane/Hound mix. I’m going to be a really sweet BIG boy.  

I’m just a happy go lucky, go with the flow kind of fella?. I’m kinda clumsy with my huge feet. I get along with all my foster brothers and sisters. Some are smaller than me and some are bigger (for now).  I need a home with older kids ( if any) at least 10 years or older. I don’t do well with humans smaller than me. I would probably do best in a home with a sibling because I love to play with my buddies.

Nylabones are a must. I love to chew on toys and keep my teeth clean. Ice cubes are one of my favorite treats. I use the doggy door to go outside and do my business. I stay in my crate while my foster parents are at work but they let me stay out at night because I do really good. I mind really good and want you to be pleased. I love attention. 

I have had all of my shots and heart worm preventative. I am neutered and microchipped. My adoption fee is $150. Try me on a home visit for a week. I will melt you with my droopy eyes. I’m ready to find my forever family and start the new year right.
